# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: strain-biology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] Rodents have been employed in biomedical experimentation from the 1650s.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] Rodent studies up to the early 19th century were mainly physiological or toxicological.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] The first rodent behavioral study was carried out in 1822, a purely observational study, while quantitative rodent behavioral testing began in the late 19th century.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] Currently, rodents are commonly used in animal testing for physiological, pathological and behavioral scientific studies, particularly mice and rats, but also guinea pigs, hamsters, gerbils and others.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] Mice are the most commonly used vertebrate species, due to their availability, size, low cost, ease of handling, and fast reproduction rate.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] In the UK in 2015, there were 3.33 million procedures on rodents (80% of total procedures that year).
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] The most common species used were mice (3.03 million procedures, or 73% of the total) and rats (268,522, or 6.5%).
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] In the U.S., the numbers of rats and mice used are not reported, but estimates range from around 11 million to approximately 100 million.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] In 2000, the Federal Research Division, Library of Congress, published the results of an analysis of its Rats/Mice/and Birds Database: Researchers, Breeders, Transporters, and Exhibitors.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] Mice are the most commonly used vertebrate species, popular because of their availability, size, low cost, ease of handling, and fast reproduction rate.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] Mice are quick to reach sexual maturity, as well as quick to gestate, where labs can have a new generation every three weeks as well as a relatively short lifespan of two years.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] They are widely considered to be the prime model of inherited human disease and share 99% of their genes with humans.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] With the advent of genetic engineering technology, genetically modified mice can be generated to order and can cost hundreds of dollars each.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] Transgenic animal production consists of injecting each construct into 300–350 eggs, typically representing three days' work.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] Twenty to fifty mice will normally be born from this number of injected eggs.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] These animals are screened for the presence of the transgene by a polymerase chain reaction genotyping assay.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] The number of transgenic animals typically varies from two to eight.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] Chimeric mouse production consists of injecting embryonic stem cells provided by the investigator into 150–175 blastocysts, representing three days of work.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] Thirty to fifty live mice are normally born from this number of injected blastocysts.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] Normally, the skin color of the mice from which the host blastocysts are derived is different from that of the strain used to produce the embryonic stem cells.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] Typically two to six mice will have skin and hair with greater than seventy percent ES cell contribution, indicating a good chance for embryonic stem cell contribution to the germline.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] Golden or Syrian hamsters (*Mesocricetus auratus*) are used to model the human medical conditions including various cancers, metabolic diseases, non-cancer respiratory diseases, cardiovascular diseases, infectious diseases, and general health concerns.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] In 2006–07, Syrian hamsters accounted for 19% of the total animal research participants in the United States.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] Rodents such as rats are the most common model in researching effects of cardiovascular disease, as the effects on rodents mimic those in humans.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] Rats have also been used as tools in research to try to find if there is a difference in the effects of cocaine on adults versus adolescents.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] While mice, rats and other rodents are by far the most widely used animals in biomedical research, recent studies have highlighted their limitations.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] For example, the utility of the use of rodents in testing for sepsis, burns, inflammation, stroke, ALS, Alzheimer's, diabetes, cancer, multiple sclerosis, Parkinson's disease and other illnesses has been called into question by a number of researchers.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] Regarding experiments on mice in particular, some researchers have complained that "years and billions of dollars have been wasted following false leads" as a result of a preoccupation with the use of these animals in studies.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] Laboratory mice reared in specific-pathogen-free (SPF) conditions usually have a rather immature immune system with a deficit of memory T cells.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] These mice may have limited diversity of the microbiota, which directly affects the immune system and the development of pathological conditions.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] Moreover, persistent virus infections (for example, herpesviruses) are activated in humans, but not in SPF mice, with septic complications and may change the resistance to bacterial coinfections.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] "Dirty" mice are possibly better suitable for mimicking human pathologies.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] In addition, inbred mouse strains are used in the overwhelming majority of studies, while the human population is heterogeneous, pointing to the importance of studies in interstrain hybrid, outbred, and nonlinear mice.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] For example, researchers have found that many rats and mice in laboratories are obese from excess food and minimal exercise which alters their physiology and drug metabolism.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] Many laboratory animals, including mice and rats, are chronically stressed which can also negatively affect research outcomes and the ability to accurately extrapolate findings to humans.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] Researchers have also noted that many studies involving mice, rats and other rodents are poorly designed, leading to questionable findings.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] One explanation for deficiencies in studies of rodents housed in laboratory cages is that they lack access to environmental agency and thus the ongoing freedom to make decisions and experience their consequences.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] By housing rodents under extreme impoverished conditions, these captive animals bear diminished resemblance to humans or their wild conspecifics.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] Some studies suggests that inadequate published data in animal testing may result in irreproducible research, with missing details about how experiments are done are omitted from published papers or differences in testing that may introduce bias.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] Examples of hidden bias include a 2014 study from McGill University in Montreal, Canada, which suggests that mice handled by men rather than women showed higher stress levels.
[src:strain-biology/animal-testing-on-rodents] Another study in 2016 suggested that gut microbiomes in mice may have an impact upon scientific research.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-genetics] The ***Annual Review of Genetics*** is an annual peer-reviewed scientific review journal published by Annual Reviews.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-genetics] It was established in 1967 and covers all topics related to the genetics of viruses, bacteria, fungi, plants, and animals, including humans.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-genetics] The current editor is Tatjana Piotrowski.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-genetics] As of 2023, it is being published as open access, under the Subscribe to Open model.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-genetics] As of 2025, *Journal Citation Reports* gives the journal a 2024 impact factor of 8.6, ranking it tenth out of 191 journals in the category "Genetics & Heredity".
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-genetics] In 1965, the nonprofit publisher Annual Reviews surveyed geneticists to determine if there was a need for an annual journal that published review articles about recent developments in the field of genetics.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-genetics] Responses to the survey were favorable, with the first volume of the *Annual Review of Genetics* published two years later in 1967.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-genetics] As of 2020, it was published both in print and electronically.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-genetics] It defines its scope as covering various aspects of genetics, including molecular, cell, and developmental biology; behavioral genetics, population genetics, chromosome structure and transmission, gene function and expression, mutation and DNA repair, genomics, and immunogenetics.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-genetics] Various organisms are considered, including viruses, bacteria, fungi, plants, and animals.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-genetics] It is abstracted and indexed in Scopus, Science Citation Index Expanded, MEDLINE, Embase, and Academic Search, among others.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-genetics] The *Annual Review of Genetics* is helmed by the editor or the co-editors.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-genetics] The editor is assisted by the editorial committee, which includes associate editors, regular members, and occasionally guest editors.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-genetics] Guest members participate at the invitation of the editor, and serve terms of one year.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-genetics] All other members of the editorial committee are appointed by the Annual Reviews board of directors and serve five-year terms.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-genetics] The editorial committee determines which topics should be included in each volume and solicits reviews from qualified authors.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-genetics] Unsolicited manuscripts are not accepted.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-genetics] Peer review of accepted manuscripts is undertaken by the editorial committee.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-genetics] Dates indicate publication years in which someone was credited as a lead editor or co-editor of a journal volume.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-genetics] The planning process for a volume begins well before the volume appears, so appointment to the position of lead editor generally occurred prior to the first year shown here.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-genetics] An editor who has retired or died may be credited as a lead editor of a volume that they helped to plan, even if it is published after their retirement or death.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-immunology] The ***Annual Review of Immunology*** is a peer-reviewed scientific journal published by Annual Reviews.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-immunology] It releases an annual volume of review articles relevant to the field of immunology.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-immunology] It was first published in 1983 with inaugural editor William E.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-immunology] Paul; Paul remained editor for the journal's first thirty years.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-immunology] As of 2023, *Annual Review of Immunology* is being published as open access, under the Subscribe to Open model.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-immunology] As of 2025, *Journal Citation Reports* gives the journal a 2024 impact factor of 33.3, ranking it second of 183 journals in the category "Immunology".
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-immunology] During the 1982 Midwinter Conference of Immunologists at the Asilomar Conference Grounds, a meeting of prominent immunologists was convened to discuss the need for a new journal that published review articles about immunological topics.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-immunology] Interest was high, with many meeting attendees agreeing that such a journal would be useful and offering to write a review for the first volume.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-immunology] The *Annual Review of Immunology* was first published in 1983, making it the twenty-fifth journal title published by the nonprofit publisher Annual Reviews.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-immunology] As of 2021, it is published both online and in print.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-immunology] Some of its articles are available online prior to the volume publication date.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-immunology] Also of interest is immune control of cancer, immunodeficiency, and autoimmune diseases.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-immunology] It is abstracted and indexed in Scopus, Science Citation Index Expanded, MEDLINE, EMBASE, Chemical Abstracts Core, and Academic Search, among others.
[src:strain-biology/annual-review-of-immunology] The *Annual Review of Immunology* is helmed by the editor or the co-editors.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaea were initially classified as bacteria, receiving the name archaebacteria (/ˌɑːrkibækˈtɪəriə/, in the Archaebacteria kingdom), but this term has fallen out of use.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaeal cells have unique properties distinguishing them from Bacteria and Eukaryota, including: cell membranes made of ether-linked lipids; metabolisms such as methanogenesis; and a unique motility structure known as an archaellum.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaea are further divided into multiple recognized phyla.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Classification is difficult because most have not been isolated in a laboratory and have been identified only by their gene sequences in environmental samples.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] They have not been observed to produce endospores.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaea are often similar to bacteria in size and shape, although a few have very different shapes, such as the flat, square cells of *Haloquadratum walsbyi*.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Despite this, archaea possess genes and several metabolic pathways that are more closely related to those of eukaryotes, notably for the enzymes involved in transcription and translation.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Other aspects of archaeal biochemistry are unique, such as their reliance on ether lipids in their cell membranes, including archaeols.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaea use more diverse energy sources than eukaryotes, ranging from organic compounds such as sugars, to ammonia, metal ions or even hydrogen gas.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The salt-tolerant Halobacteria use sunlight as an energy source, and other species of archaea fix carbon (autotrophy), but unlike cyanobacteria, no known species of archaea does both.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaea reproduce asexually by binary fission, fragmentation, or budding; unlike bacteria, no known species of Archaea form endospores.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The first observed archaea were extremophiles, living in extreme environments such as hot springs and salt lakes with no other organisms.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Improved molecular detection tools led to the discovery of archaea in almost every habitat, including soil, oceans, and marshlands.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaea are particularly numerous in the oceans, and the archaea in plankton may be one of the most abundant groups of organisms on the planet.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaea are a major part of Earth's life.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] They are part of the microbiota of all organisms.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] In the human microbiome, they are important in the gut, mouth, and on the skin.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Their morphological, metabolic, and geographical diversity permits them to play multiple ecological roles: carbon fixation; nitrogen cycling; organic compound turnover; and maintaining microbial symbiotic and syntrophic communities, for example.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] As of 2024, only one species of archaea has been found to be parasitic; many are mutualists or commensals, such as the methanogens (methane-producers) that inhabit the gastrointestinal tract in humans and ruminants, where their vast numbers facilitate digestion.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Methanogens are used in biogas production and sewage treatment, while biotechnology exploits enzymes from extremophile archaea that can endure high temperatures and organic solvents.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] For much of the 20th century, prokaryotes were regarded as a single group of organisms and classified based on their biochemistry, morphology and metabolism.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Microbiologists tried to classify microorganisms based on the structures of their cell walls, their shapes, and the substances they consume.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] In 1965, Emile Zuckerkandl and Linus Pauling instead proposed using the sequences of the genes in different prokaryotes to work out how they are related to each other.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] This phylogenetic approach is the main method used today.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The first archaea to be isolated and grown in pure culture were methane-producing species in the genera Methanobacterium and Methanococcus in the 1930s and 1940s, although at the time, they were classified as bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaea were first classified separately from bacteria in 1977 by Carl Woese and George E.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Fox, based on their ribosomal RNA (rRNA) genes.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] (At that time only the methanogens were known).
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] They called these groups the *Urkingdoms* of Archaebacteria and Eubacteria, though other researchers treated them as kingdoms or subkingdoms.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Woese and Fox gave the first evidence for Archaebacteria as a separate "line of descent": 1. lack of peptidoglycan in their cell walls, 2. two unusual coenzymes, 3. results of 16S ribosomal RNA gene sequencing.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] To emphasize this difference, Woese, Otto Kandler and Mark Wheelis later proposed reclassifying organisms into three then thought to be natural domains known as the three-domain system: the Eukarya, the Bacteria and the Archaea, in what is now known as the Woesian Revolution.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Extreme halophilic and hyperthermophilic microbes were also included in Archaea.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] For a long time, archaea were seen as extremophiles that exist only in extreme habitats such as hot springs and salt lakes, but by the end of the 20th century, archaea had been identified in non-extreme environments as well.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Today, they are known to be a large and diverse group of organisms abundantly distributed throughout nature.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] This new appreciation of the importance and ubiquity of archaea came from using polymerase chain reaction (PCR) to detect prokaryotes from environmental samples (such as water or soil) by multiplying their ribosomal genes.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] This allows the detection and identification of organisms that have not been cultured in the laboratory.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The classification of archaea, and of prokaryotes in general, is a rapidly moving and contentious field.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Current classification systems aim to organize archaea into groups of organisms that share structural features and common ancestors.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] These classifications rely heavily on the use of the sequence of ribosomal RNA genes to reveal relationships among organisms (molecular phylogenetics).
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Most of the culturable and well-investigated species of archaea are members of two main kingdoms, the Methanobacteriati and the Thermoproteati (formerly TACK).
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Other groups have been tentatively created, such as the peculiar species *Nanoarchaeum equitans* – discovered in 2003 and assigned its own phylum, the Nanoarchaeota (reassigned to Nanobdellota in 2023).
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] A new phylum "Korarchaeota" (now Thermoproteota) has also been proposed, containing a small group of unusual thermophilic species sharing features of both the main phyla.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Other detected species of archaea are only distantly related to any of these groups, such as the Archaeal Richmond Mine acidophilic nanoorganisms (ARMAN, comprising Micrarchaeota and Parvarchaeota), which were discovered in 2006 and are some of the smallest organisms known.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] A superphylum – "TACK" (now kingdom Thermoproteati) – which includes the Thaumarchaeota (now Nitrososphaerota), "Augarchaeota", Crenarchaeota (now Thermoproteota), and "Korarchaeota" (now Thermoproteota) was proposed in 2011 to be related to the origin of eukaryotes.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] In 2017, the newly discovered and newly named "Asgard" (now kingdom Promethearchaeati) superphylum was proposed to be more closely related to the original eukaryote and a sister group to Thermoproteati / "TACK".
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] In 2013, the superphylum "DPANN" (now kingdom Nanobdellati) was proposed to group "Nanoarchaeota", "Nanohaloarchaeota", Archaeal Richmond Mine acidophilic nanoorganisms (ARMAN, comprising "Micrarchaeota" and "Parvarchaeota"), and other similar archaea.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] This archaeal superphylum encompasses at least 10 different lineages and includes organisms with extremely small cell and genome sizes and limited metabolic capabilities.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Therefore, Nanobdellati/"DPANN" may include members obligately dependent on symbiotic interactions, and may even include novel parasites.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] However, other phylogenetic analyses found that Nanobdellati/"DPANN" does not form a monophyletic group, and that the apparent grouping is caused by long branch attraction (LBA), suggesting that all these lineages belong to Methanobacteriati.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The classification of archaea into species is also controversial.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Ernst Mayr's species definition – a reproductively isolated group of interbreeding organisms - does not apply, as archaea reproduce only asexually.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaea show high levels of horizontal gene transfer between lineages.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Some researchers suggest that individuals can be grouped into species-like populations given highly similar genomes and infrequent gene transfer to/from cells with less-related genomes, as in the genus *Ferroplasma*.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] On the other hand, studies in *Halorubrum* found significant genetic transfer to/from less-related populations, limiting the criterion's applicability.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Some researchers question whether such species designations have practical meaning.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Current knowledge on genetic diversity in archaeans is fragmentary, so the total number of species cannot be estimated with any accuracy.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Estimates of the number of phyla range from 18 to 23, of which only 8 have representatives that have been cultured and studied directly.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Many of these hypothesized groups are known from a single rRNA sequence, so the level of diversity remains obscure.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] This situation is also seen in the Bacteria; many uncultured microbes present similar issues with characterization.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The age of the Earth is about 4.54 billion years.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Scientific evidence suggests that life began on Earth at least 3.5 billion years ago.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The earliest evidence for life on Earth is graphite found to be biogenic in 3.7-billion-year-old metasedimentary rocks discovered in Western Greenland and microbial mat fossils found in 3.48-billion-year-old sandstone discovered in Western Australia.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] In 2015, possible remains of biotic matter were found in 4.1-billion-year-old rocks in Western Australia.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Although probable prokaryotic cell fossils date to almost 3.5 billion years ago, most prokaryotes do not have distinctive morphologies, and fossil shapes cannot be used to identify them as archaea.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Instead, chemical fossils of unique lipids are more informative because such compounds do not occur in other organisms.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Some publications suggest that archaeal or eukaryotic lipid remains are present in shales dating from 2.7 billion years ago, though such data have since been questioned.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] These lipids have also been detected in even older rocks from west Greenland.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The oldest such traces come from the Isua district, which includes Earth's oldest known sediments, formed 3.8 billion years ago.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The archaeal lineage may be the most ancient that exists on Earth.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Woese argued that the bacteria, archaea, and eukaryotes represent separate lines of descent that diverged early on from an ancestral colony of organisms.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] One possibility is that this occurred before the evolution of cells, when the lack of a typical cell membrane allowed unrestricted lateral gene transfer, and that the common ancestors of the three domains arose by fixation of specific subsets of genes.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] It is possible that the last common ancestor of bacteria and archaea was a thermophile, which raises the possibility that lower temperatures are "extreme environments" for archaea, and organisms that live in cooler environments appeared only later.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Since archaea and bacteria are no more related to each other than they are to eukaryotes, the term *prokaryote* may suggest a false similarity between them.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] However, structural and functional similarities between lineages often occur because of shared ancestral traits or evolutionary convergence.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] These similarities are known as a *grade*, and prokaryotes are best thought of as a grade of life, characterized by such features as an absence of membrane-bound organelles.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The following table compares some major characteristics of the three domains, to illustrate their similarities and differences.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaea were split off as a third domain because of the large differences in their ribosomal RNA structure.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The particular molecule 16S rRNA is key to the production of proteins in all organisms.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Because this function is so central to life, organisms with mutations in their 16S rRNA are unlikely to survive, leading to great (but not absolute) stability in the structure of this polynucleotide over generations.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] 16S rRNA is large enough to show organism-specific variations, but still small enough to be compared quickly.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] In 1977, Carl Woese, a microbiologist studying the genetic sequences of organisms, developed a new comparison method that involved splitting the RNA into fragments that could be sorted and compared with other fragments from other organisms.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The more similar the patterns between species, the more closely they are related.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Woese used his new rRNA comparison method to categorize and contrast different organisms.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] He compared a variety of species and happened upon a group of methanogens with rRNA vastly different from any known prokaryotes or eukaryotes.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] These methanogens were much more similar to each other than to other organisms, leading Woese to propose the new domain of Archaea.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] His experiments showed that the archaea were genetically more similar to eukaryotes than prokaryotes, even though they were more similar to prokaryotes in structure.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] This led to the conclusion that Archaea and Eukarya shared a common ancestor more recent than Eukarya and Bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The development of the nucleus occurred after the split between Bacteria and this common ancestor.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] One property unique to archaea is the abundant use of ether-linked lipids in their cell membranes.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Ether linkages are more chemically stable than the ester linkages found in bacteria and eukarya, which may be a contributing factor to the ability of many archaea to survive in extreme environments that place heavy stress on cell membranes, such as extreme heat and salinity.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Comparative analysis of archaeal genomes has also identified several molecular conserved signature indels and signature proteins uniquely present in either all archaea or different main groups within archaea.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Another unique feature of archaea, found in no other organisms, is methanogenesis (the metabolic production of methane).
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Methanogenic archaea play a pivotal role in ecosystems with organisms that derive energy from oxidation of methane, many of which are bacteria, as they are often a major source of methane in such environments and can play a role as primary producers.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Methanogens also play a critical role in the carbon cycle, breaking down organic carbon into methane, which is also a major greenhouse gas.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] This difference in the biochemical structure of Bacteria and Archaea has been explained by researchers through evolutionary processes.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] It is theorized that both domains originated at deep sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] At least twice, microbes evolved lipid biosynthesis and cell wall biochemistry.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] It has been suggested that the last universal common ancestor was a non-free-living organism.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] It may have had a permeable membrane composed of bacterial simple chain amphiphiles (fatty acids), including archaeal simple chain amphiphiles (isoprenoids).
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] These stabilize fatty acid membranes in seawater; this property may have driven the divergence of bacterial and archaeal membranes, "with the later biosynthesis of phospholipids giving rise to the unique G1P and G3P headgroups of archaea and bacteria respectively.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] If so, the properties conferred by membrane isoprenoids place the lipid divide as early as the origin of life".
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The relationships among the three domains are of central importance for understanding the origin of life.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Most of the metabolic pathways, which are the object of the majority of an organism's genes, are common between Archaea and Bacteria, while most genes involved in gene expression are common between Archaea and Eukarya.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Within prokaryotes, archaeal cell structure is most similar to that of Gram-positive bacteria, largely because both have a single lipid bilayer and usually contain a thick sacculus (exoskeleton) of varying chemical composition.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] In some phylogenetic trees based upon different gene / protein sequences of prokaryotic homologs, the archaeal homologs are more closely related to those of gram-positive bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaea and gram-positive bacteria also share conserved indels in a number of important proteins, such as Hsp70 and glutamine synthetase I; but the phylogeny of these genes was interpreted to reveal inter-domain gene transfer, and might not reflect the organismal relationship(s).
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] It has been proposed that the archaea evolved from Gram-positive bacteria in response to antibiotic selection pressure.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] This is suggested by the observation that archaea are resistant to a wide variety of antibiotics that are produced primarily by Gram-positive bacteria, and that these antibiotics act primarily on the genes that distinguish archaea from bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The proposal is that the selective pressure towards resistance generated by the gram-positive antibiotics was eventually sufficient to cause extensive changes in many of the antibiotics' target genes, and that these strains represented the common ancestors of present-day Archaea.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] This proposal is also supported by other work investigating protein structural relationships and studies that suggest that gram-positive bacteria may constitute the earliest branching lineages within the prokaryotes.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The evolutionary relationship between archaea and eukaryotes remains unclear.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Aside from the similarities in cell structure and function that are discussed below, many genetic trees group the two.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The standard hypothesis states that the ancestor of the eukaryotes diverged early from the Archaea, and that eukaryotes arose through symbiogenesis, the fusion of an archaean and a eubacterium, which formed the mitochondria; this hypothesis explains the genetic similarities between the groups.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The eocyte hypothesis instead posits that Eukaryota emerged relatively late from the Archaea.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] A lineage of archaea discovered in 2015, *Lokiarchaeum* (of the proposed new phylum "Lokiarchaeota"), named for a hydrothermal vent called Loki's Castle in the Arctic Ocean, was found to be the most closely related to eukaryotes known at that time.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] It has been called a transitional organism between prokaryotes and eukaryotes.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Several sister phyla of "Lokiarchaeota" have since been found ("Thorarchaeota", "Odinarchaeota", "Heimdallarchaeota"), all together comprising a newly proposed supergroup "Asgard".
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaea range from 0.1 micrometers (μm) to over 15 μm in diameter, and commonly occur as spheres, rods, spirals or plates.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Morphologies in the Thermoproteota also include irregularly shaped lobed cells in *Sulfolobus*, needle-like filaments that are less than half a micrometer in diameter in *Thermofilum*, and almost perfectly rectangular rods in *Thermoproteus* and *Pyrobaculum*.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaea in the genus *Haloquadratum* such as *Haloquadratum walsbyi* are flat, square specimens that live in hypersaline pools.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] These unusual shapes are probably maintained by both their cell walls and a prokaryotic cytoskeleton.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Proteins related to the cytoskeleton components of other organisms exist in archaea, and filaments form within their cells, but in contrast with other organisms, these cellular structures are poorly understood.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] In *Thermoplasma* and *Ferroplasma* the lack of a cell wall means that the cells have irregular shapes, and can resemble amoebae.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Some species form aggregates or filaments of cells up to 200 μm long.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] These organisms can be prominent in biofilms.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Notably, aggregates of *Thermococcus coalescens* cells fuse together in culture, forming single giant cells.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaea in the genus *Pyrodictium* produce an elaborate multicell colony involving arrays of long, thin hollow tubes called *cannulae* that stick out from the cells' surfaces and connect them into a dense bush-like agglomeration.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The function of these cannulae is not settled, but they may allow communication or nutrient exchange with neighbors.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Multi-species colonies exist, such as the "string-of-pearls" community that was discovered in 2001 in a German swamp.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Round whitish colonies of a novel Methanobacteriati species are spaced along thin filaments that can range up to 15 centimetres (5.9 in) long; these filaments are made of a particular bacteria species.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaea and bacteria have generally similar cell structure, but cell composition and organization set the archaea apart.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Like bacteria, archaea lack interior membranes and organelles.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Like bacteria, the cell membranes of archaea are usually bounded by a cell wall and they swim using one or more flagella.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Structurally, archaea are most similar to gram-positive bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Most have a single plasma membrane and cell wall, and lack a periplasmic space; the exception to this general rule is *Ignicoccus*, which possess a particularly large periplasm that contains membrane-bound vesicles and is enclosed by an outer membrane.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Most archaea (but not *Thermoplasma* and *Ferroplasma*) possess a cell wall.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] In most archaea, the wall is assembled from surface-layer proteins, which form an S-layer.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] An S-layer is a rigid array of protein molecules that cover the outside of the cell (like chain mail).
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] This layer provides both chemical and physical protection, and can prevent macromolecules from contacting the cell membrane.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Unlike bacteria, archaea lack peptidoglycan in their cell walls.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaeal flagella are known as archaella, that operate like bacterial flagella – their long stalks are driven by rotatory motors at the base.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] These motors are powered by a proton gradient across the membrane, but archaella are notably different in composition and development.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The two types of flagella evolved from different ancestors.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The bacterial flagellum shares a common ancestor with the type III secretion system, while archaeal flagella appear to have evolved from bacterial type IV pili.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] In contrast with the bacterial flagellum, which is hollow and assembled by subunits moving up the central pore to the tip of the flagella, archaeal flagella are synthesized by adding subunits at the base.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaeal membranes are made of different molecules from those in bacterial and eukaryotic membranes.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] In all organisms, cell membranes are made of molecules known as phospholipids.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] These molecules possess both a polar part that dissolves in water (the phosphate "head"), and a "greasy" non-polar part that does not (the lipid tail).
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] These dissimilar parts are connected by a glycerol moiety.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] In water, phospholipids cluster, with the heads facing the water and the tails facing away from it.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The major structure in cell membranes is a double layer of these phospholipids, which is called a lipid bilayer.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaea exhibit a great variety of chemical reactions in their metabolism and use many sources of energy.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] These reactions are classified into nutritional groups, depending on energy and carbon sources.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Some archaea obtain energy from inorganic compounds such as sulfur or ammonia (they are chemotrophs).
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] These include nitrifiers, methanogens and anaerobic methane oxidisers.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] In these reactions, one compound passes electrons to another (in a redox reaction), releasing energy to fuel the cell's activities.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] One compound acts as an electron donor and one as an electron acceptor.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The energy released is used to generate adenosine triphosphate (ATP) through chemiosmosis, the same basic process that happens in the mitochondrion of eukaryotic cells.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Other groups of archaea use sunlight as a source of energy (they are phototrophs), but oxygen–generating photosynthesis does not occur in any of these organisms.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Many basic metabolic pathways are shared among all forms of life; for example, archaea use a modified form of glycolysis (the Entner–Doudoroff pathway) and either a complete or partial citric acid cycle.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] These similarities to other organisms probably reflect both early origins in the history of life and their high level of efficiency.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Some Methanobacteriati are methanogens (archaea that produce methane as a result of metabolism) living in anaerobic environments, such as swamps.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] This form of metabolism evolved early, and it is even possible that the first free-living organism was a methanogen.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] A common reaction involves the use of carbon dioxide as an electron acceptor to oxidize hydrogen.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Methanogenesis involves a range of coenzymes that are unique to these archaea, such as coenzyme M and methanofuran.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Other organic compounds such as alcohols, acetic acid or formic acid are used as alternative electron acceptors by methanogens.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] These reactions are common in gut-dwelling archaea.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Acetic acid is also broken down into methane and carbon dioxide directly, by *acetotrophic* archaea.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] These acetotrophs are archaea in the order Methanosarcinales, and are a major part of the communities of microorganisms that produce biogas.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Other archaea use CO 2 in the atmosphere as a source of carbon, in a process called carbon fixation (they are autotrophs).
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] This process involves either a highly modified form of the Calvin cycle or another metabolic pathway called the 3-hydroxypropionate / 4-hydroxybutyrate cycle.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The Thermoproteota also use the reverse Krebs cycle while the Methanobacteriati also use the reductive acetyl-CoA pathway.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Carbon fixation is powered by inorganic energy sources.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] No known archaea carry out photosynthesis.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaeal energy sources are extremely diverse, and range from the oxidation of ammonia by the Nitrosopumilales to the oxidation of hydrogen sulfide or elemental sulfur by species of *Sulfolobus*, using either oxygen or metal ions as electron acceptors.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Phototrophic archaea use light to produce chemical energy in the form of ATP.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] In the Halobacteria, light-activated ion pumps like bacteriorhodopsin and halorhodopsin generate ion gradients by pumping ions out of and into the cell across the plasma membrane.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The energy stored in these electrochemical gradients is then converted into ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] This process is a form of photophosphorylation.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The ability of these light-driven pumps to move ions across membranes depends on light-driven changes in the structure of a retinol cofactor buried in the center of the protein.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaea usually have a single circular chromosome, but many euryarchaea have been shown to bear multiple copies of this chromosome.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The largest known archaeal genome as of 2002 was 5,751,492 base pairs in *Methanosarcina acetivorans*.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The tiny 490,885 base-pair genome of *Nanoarchaeum equitans* is one-tenth of this size and the smallest archaeal genome known; it is estimated to contain only 537 protein-encoding genes.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Smaller independent pieces of DNA, called *plasmids*, are also found in archaea.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Plasmids may be transferred between cells by physical contact, in a process that may be similar to bacterial conjugation.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaea are genetically distinct from bacteria and eukaryotes, with up to 15% of the proteins encoded by any one archaeal genome being unique to the domain, although most of these unique genes have no known function.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Of the remainder of the unique proteins that have an identified function, most belong to the Methanobacteriati and are involved in methanogenesis.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The proteins that archaea, bacteria and eukaryotes share form a common core of cell function, relating mostly to transcription, translation, and nucleotide metabolism.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Other characteristic archaeal features are the organization of genes of related function – such as enzymes that catalyze steps in the same metabolic pathway into novel operons, and large differences in tRNA genes and their aminoacyl tRNA synthetases.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Transcription in archaea more closely resembles eukaryotic than bacterial transcription, with the archaeal RNA polymerase being very close to its equivalent in eukaryotes, while archaeal translation shows signs of both bacterial and eukaryotic equivalents.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Post-transcriptional modification is simpler than in eukaryotes, since most archaeal genes lack introns, although there are many introns in their transfer RNA and ribosomal RNA genes, and introns may occur in a few protein-encoding genes.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] When the hyperthermophilic archaea *Sulfolobus solfataricus* and *Sulfolobus acidocaldarius* are exposed to DNA-damaging UV irradiation or to the agents bleomycin or mitomycin C, species-specific cellular aggregation is induced.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Aggregation in *S. solfataricus* could not be induced by other physical stressors, such as pH or temperature shift, suggesting that aggregation is induced specifically by DNA damage.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Ajon et al. showed that UV-induced cellular aggregation mediates chromosomal marker exchange with high frequency in *S. acidocaldarius*.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Recombination rates exceeded those of uninduced cultures by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Frols et al. and Ajon et al. hypothesized that cellular aggregation enhances species-specific DNA transfer between *Sulfolobus* cells in order to provide increased repair of damaged DNA by means of homologous recombination.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] This response may be a primitive form of sexual interaction similar to the more well-studied bacterial transformation systems that are also associated with species-specific DNA transfer between cells leading to homologous recombinational repair of DNA damage.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaea are the target of a number of viruses in a diverse virosphere distinct from bacterial and eukaryotic viruses.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] They have been organized into 15–18 DNA-based families so far, but multiple species remain un-isolated and await classification.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] These families can be informally divided into two groups: archaea-specific and cosmopolitan.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaeal-specific viruses target only archaean species and currently include 12 families.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Numerous unique, previously unidentified viral structures have been observed in this group, including: bottle-shaped, spindle-shaped, coil-shaped, and droplet-shaped viruses.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] While the reproductive cycles and genomic mechanisms of archaea-specific species may be similar to other viruses, they bear unique characteristics that were specifically developed due to the morphology of host cells they infect.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Their virus release mechanisms differ from that of other phages.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Bacteriophages generally undergo either lytic pathways, lysogenic pathways, or (rarely) a mix of the two.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Most archaea-specific viral strains maintain a stable, somewhat lysogenic, relationship with their hosts – appearing as a chronic infection.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] This involves the gradual, and continuous, production and release of virions without killing the host cell.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Prangishyili (2013) noted that it has been hypothesized that tailed archaeal phages originated from bacteriophages capable of infecting haloarchaeal species.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] If the hypothesis is correct, it can be concluded that other double-stranded DNA viruses that make up the rest of the archaea-specific group are their own unique group in the global viral community.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] (2018) states that the high levels of horizontal gene transfer, rapid mutation rates in viral genomes, and lack of universal gene sequences have led researchers to perceive the evolutionary pathway of archaeal viruses as a network.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The lack of similarities among phylogenetic markers in this network and the global virosphere, as well as external linkages to non-viral elements, may suggest that some species of archaea specific viruses evolved from non-viral mobile genetic elements (MGE).
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] These viruses have been studied in most detail in thermophilics, particularly the orders Sulfolobales and Thermoproteales.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Two groups of single-stranded DNA viruses that infect archaea have been recently isolated.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] One group is exemplified by the *Halorubrum pleomorphic virus 1* (*Pleolipoviridae*) infecting halophilic archaea, and the other one by the *Aeropyrum coil-shaped virus* (*Spiraviridae*) infecting a hyperthermophilic (optimal growth at 90–95 °C) host.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Notably, the latter virus has the largest currently reported ssDNA genome.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Defenses against these viruses may involve RNA interference from repetitive DNA sequences that are related to the genes of the viruses.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaea reproduce asexually by binary or multiple fission, fragmentation, or budding; mitosis and meiosis do not occur, so if a species of archaea exists in more than one form, all have the same genetic material.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Cell division is controlled in a cell cycle; after the cell's chromosome is replicated and the two daughter chromosomes separate, the cell divides.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] In the genus *Sulfolobus*, the cycle has characteristics that are similar to both bacterial and eukaryotic systems.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] The chromosomes replicate from multiple starting points (origins of replication) using DNA polymerases that resemble the equivalent eukaryotic enzymes.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] In Methanobacteriati the cell division protein FtsZ, which forms a contracting ring around the cell, and the components of the septum that is constructed across the center of the cell, are similar to their bacterial equivalents.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] In cren- and thaumarchaea, the cell division machinery Cdv fulfills a similar role.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] This machinery is related to the eukaryotic ESCRT-III machinery which, while best known for its role in cell sorting, also has been seen to fulfill a role in separation between divided cell, suggesting an ancestral role in cell division.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Both bacteria and eukaryotes, but not archaea, make spores.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Quorum sensing was originally thought to not exist in Archaea, but recent studies have shown evidence of some species being able to perform cross-talk through quorum sensing.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Other studies have shown syntrophic interactions between archaea and bacteria during biofilm growth.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Although research is limited in archaeal quorum sensing, some studies have uncovered LuxR proteins in archaeal species, displaying similarities with bacteria LuxR, and ultimately allowing for the detection of small molecules that are used in high density communication.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Similarly to bacteria, Archaea LuxR solos have shown to bind to AHLs (lactones) and non-AHLs ligans, which is a large part in performing intraspecies, interspecies, and interkingdom communication through quorum sensing.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Archaea are known to form biofilms, a common strategy among microorganisms.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Quorum sensing is thought to play a role in Archaeal biofilm formation, but less is known about Archaeal quorum sensing than Bacterial quorum sensing.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Some Archaea have been observed to form biofilms when the pH is a specific value, without necessarily relying on quorum sensing for instance.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] These biofilms are sessile communities of micro-organisms (they can contain multiple different species) that produce extracellular polymeric substances, which are used to create a matrix, within which the micro-organisms can grow.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Biofilms are beneficial as they: protect organisms from abiotic stresses; facilitate horizontal gene transfer; and enable syntropy to take place.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Biofilm formation has a number of stages: attachment; micro-colony formation; maturation; and dispersal.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] During the attachment phase the Archaea are reversibly attached to a surface by type-4 pili and archaella.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Some Archaea possess other structures involved in attachment such as hami; fimbriae; or cannulae.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] During the micro colony phase, the extracellular polymeric substance matrix is produced, and numerous archaea have been observed to produce pills and nanowires between cells.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] During the maturation phase the matrix takes on a sophisticated architecture, such as including pathways for waste to exit the biofilms.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Different archaea have been observed to produce biofilms with different architectures.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p01] Finally, dispersal can take place, where cells begin to leave the biofilm, this process has been observed in Archaea but the mechanisms behind it are not understood.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Archaea exist in a broad range of habitats, are recognized as a major part of global ecosystems, and may represent about 20% of microbial cells in the oceans as well as a large number of cells in sea floor sediment.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] However, the first-discovered archaeans were extremophiles.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Indeed, some archaea survive high temperatures, often above 100 °C (212 °F), as found in geysers, black smokers, and oil wells.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Other common habitats include very cold habitats and highly saline, acidic, or alkaline water, but archaea include mesophiles that grow in mild conditions, in swamps and marshland, sewage, the oceans, the intestinal tract of animals, and soils.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Similar to PGPR, Archaea are considered a source of plant growth promotion as well.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Extremophile archaea are members of four main physiological groups.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] These are the halophiles, thermophiles, alkaliphiles, and acidophiles.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] These groups are not comprehensive or phylum-specific, nor are they mutually exclusive, since some archaea belong to several groups.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Nonetheless, they are a useful starting point for classification.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Halophiles, including the genus *Halobacterium*, live in extremely saline environments such as salt lakes and outnumber their bacterial counterparts at salinities greater than 20–25%.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Thermophiles grow best at temperatures above 45 °C (113 °F), in places such as hot springs; *hyperthermophilic* archaea grow optimally at temperatures greater than 80 °C (176 °F).
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] The archaeal *Methanopyrus kandleri* Strain 116 can even reproduce at 122 °C (252 °F), the highest recorded temperature of any organism.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Other archaea exist in very acidic or alkaline conditions.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] For example, one of the most extreme archaean acidophiles is *Picrophilus torridus*, which grows at pH 0, which is equivalent to thriving in 1.2 molar sulfuric acid.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] This resistance to extreme environments has made archaea the focus of speculation about the possible properties of extraterrestrial life.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Some extremophile habitats are not dissimilar to those on Mars, leading to the suggestion that viable microbes could be transferred between planets in meteorites.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Recently, several studies have shown that archaea exist not only in mesophilic and thermophilic environments but are also present, sometimes in high numbers, at low temperatures as well.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] For example, archaea are common in cold oceanic environments such as polar seas.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Even more significant are the large numbers of archaea found throughout the world's oceans in non-extreme habitats among the plankton community (as part of the picoplankton).
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Although these archaea can be present in extremely high numbers (up to 40% of the microbial biomass), almost none of these species have been isolated and studied in pure culture.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Consequently, our understanding of the role of archaea in ocean ecology is rudimentary, so their full influence on global biogeochemical cycles remains largely unexplored.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Some marine Thermoproteota are capable of nitrification, suggesting these organisms may affect the oceanic nitrogen cycle, although these oceanic Thermoproteota may also use other sources of energy.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Vast numbers of archaea are also found in the sediments that cover the sea floor, with these organisms making up at least 12.8%, and in many places, the majority of living cells at depths over 1 meter below the ocean bottom.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Archaea recycle elements such as carbon, nitrogen, and sulfur through their various habitats.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Archaea carry out many steps in the nitrogen cycle.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] This includes both reactions that remove nitrogen from ecosystems (such as nitrate-based respiration and denitrification) as well as processes that introduce nitrogen (such as nitrate assimilation and nitrogen fixation).
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Researchers recently discovered archaeal involvement in ammonia oxidation reactions.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] These reactions are particularly important in the oceans.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] The archaea also appear crucial for ammonia oxidation in soils.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] They produce nitrite, which other microbes then oxidize to nitrate.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Plants and other organisms consume the latter.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] In the carbon cycle, methanogen archaea remove hydrogen and play an important role in the decay of organic matter by the populations of microorganisms that act as decomposers in anaerobic ecosystems, such as sediments, marshes, and sewage-treatment works.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] The well-characterized interactions between archaea and other organisms are either mutual or commensal.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Mutualism is an interaction between individuals of different species that results in positive (beneficial) effects on per capita reproduction and/or survival of the interacting populations.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] One well-understood example of mutualism is the interaction between protozoa and methanogenic archaea in the digestive tracts of animals that digest cellulose, such as ruminants and termites.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] In these anaerobic environments, protozoa break down plant cellulose to obtain energy.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] This process releases hydrogen as a waste product, but high levels of hydrogen reduce energy production.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] When methanogens convert hydrogen to methane, protozoa benefit from more energy.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] In anaerobic protozoa, such as *Plagiopyla frontata*, *Trimyema*, *Heterometopus* and *Metopus contortus*, archaea reside inside the protozoa and consume hydrogen produced in their hydrogenosomes.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Archaea associate with larger organisms, too.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] For example, the marine archaean *Cenarchaeum symbiosum* is an endosymbiont of the sponge *Axinella mexicana*.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Some archaea are commensals, benefiting from an association without helping or harming the other organism.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] For example, the methanogen *Methanobrevibacter smithii* is by far the most common archaean in the human flora, making up about one in ten of the prokaryotes in the human gut.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] In termites and in humans, these methanogens may in fact be mutualists, interacting with other microbes in the gut to aid digestion.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Archaean communities associate with a range of other organisms, such as on the surface of corals, and in the region of soil that surrounds plant roots (the rhizosphere).
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Although Archaea do not have a historical reputation of being pathogens, Archaea are often found with similar genomes to more common pathogens like *E. coli,* showing metabolic links and evolutionary history with today's pathogens.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Archaea have been inconsistently detected in clinical studies because of the lack of categorization of Archaea into more specific species.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] The reduced genome of *Candidatus* Sukunaarchaeum mirabile suggests it is a specialized parasite highly dependant on its dinoflagellate host.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Extremophile archaea, particularly those resistant either to heat or to extremes of acidity and alkalinity, are a source of enzymes that function under these harsh conditions.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] For example, thermostable DNA polymerases, such as the Pfu DNA polymerase from *Pyrococcus furiosus*, revolutionized molecular biology by allowing the polymerase chain reaction to be used in research as a simple and rapid technique for cloning DNA.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] In industry, amylases, galactosidases and pullulanases in other species of *Pyrococcus* that function at over 100 °C (212 °F) allow food processing at high temperatures, such as the production of low lactose milk and whey.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Enzymes from these thermophilic archaea also tend to be very stable in organic solvents, allowing their use in environmentally friendly processes in green chemistry that synthesize organic compounds.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] This stability makes them easier to use in structural biology.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Consequently, the counterparts of bacterial or eukaryotic enzymes from extremophile archaea are often used in structural studies.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] In contrast with the range of applications of archaean enzymes, the use of the organisms themselves in biotechnology is less developed.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Methanogenic archaea are a vital part of sewage treatment, since they are part of the community of microorganisms that carry out anaerobic digestion and produce biogas.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] In mineral processing, acidophilic archaea display promise for the extraction of metals from ores, including gold, cobalt and copper.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] Archaea host a new class of potentially useful antibiotics.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] A few of these archaeocins have been characterized, but hundreds more are believed to exist, especially within Halobacteria and *Sulfolobus*.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] These compounds differ in structure from bacterial antibiotics, so they may have novel modes of action.
[src:strain-biology/archaea-p02] In addition, they may allow the creation of new selectable markers for use in archaeal molecular biology.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] As of 2014, there are over 30,000 sequenced bacterial genomes publicly available and thousands of metagenome projects.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Projects such as the Genomic Encyclopedia of Bacteria and Archaea (GEBA) intend to add more genomes.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] The single gene comparison is now being supplanted by more general methods.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] These methods have resulted in novel perspectives on genetic relationships that previously have only been estimated.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] A significant achievement in the second decade of bacterial genome sequencing was the production of metagenomic data, which covers all DNA present in a sample.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Previously, there were only two metagenomic projects published.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Bacteria possess a compact genome architecture distinct from eukaryotes in two important ways: bacteria show a strong correlation between genome size and number of functional genes in a genome, and those genes are structured into operons.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] The main reason for the relative density of bacterial genomes compared to eukaryotic genomes (especially multicellular eukaryotes) is the presence of noncoding DNA in the form of intergenic regions and introns.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Some notable exceptions include recently formed pathogenic bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] This was initially described in a study by Cole *et al*. in which *Mycobacterium leprae* was discovered to have a significantly higher percentage of pseudogenes to functional genes (~40%) than its free-living ancestors.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Furthermore, amongst species of bacteria, there is relatively little variation in genome size when compared with the genome sizes of other major groups of life.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Genome size is of little relevance when considering the number of functional genes in eukaryotic species.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] In bacteria, however, the strong correlation between the number of genes and the genome size makes the size of bacterial genomes an interesting topic for research and discussion.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] The general trends of bacterial evolution indicate that bacteria started as free-living organisms.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Evolutionary paths led some bacteria to become pathogens and symbionts.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] The lifestyles of bacteria play an integral role in their respective genome sizes.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Free-living bacteria have the largest genomes out of the three types of bacteria; however, they have fewer pseudogenes than bacteria that have recently acquired pathogenicity.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Facultative and recently evolved pathogenic bacteria exhibit a smaller genome size than free-living bacteria, yet they have more pseudogenes than any other form of bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Obligate bacterial symbionts or pathogens have the smallest genomes and the fewest pseudogenes of the three groups.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] The relationship between life-styles of bacteria and genome size raises questions as to the mechanisms of bacterial genome evolution.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Researchers have developed several theories to explain the patterns of genome size evolution amongst bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] As single-gene comparisons have largely given way to genome comparisons, phylogeny of bacterial genomes have improved in accuracy.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] The Average Nucleotide Identity (ANI) method quantifies genetic distance between entire genomes by taking advantage of regions of about 10,000 bp.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] With enough data from genomes of one genus, algorithms are executed to categorize species.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] This has been done for the *Pseudomonas avellanae* species in 2013 and for all sequenced bacteria and archaea since 2020.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Observed ANI values among sequences appear to have an "ANI gap" at 85–95%, suggesting that a genetic boundary suitable for defining a species concept is present.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] To extract information about bacterial genomes, core- and pan-genome sizes have been assessed for several strains of bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] In 2012, the number of core gene families was about 3000.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] However, by 2015, with an over tenfold increased in available genomes, the pan-genome has increased as well.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] There is roughly a positive correlation between the number of genomes added and the growth of the pan-genome.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] On the other hand, the core genome has remain static since 2012.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Currently, the *E. coli* pan-genome is composed of about 90,000 gene families.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] About one-third of these exist only in a single genome.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Many of these, however, are merely gene fragments and the result of calling errors.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Still, there are probably over 60,000 unique gene families in *E. coli*.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Bacteria lose a large amount of genes as they transition from free-living or facultatively parasitic life cycles to permanent host-dependent life.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Towards the lower end of the scale of bacterial genome size are the mycoplasmas and related bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Early molecular phylogenetic studies revealed that mycoplasmas represented an evolutionary derived state, contrary to prior hypotheses.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Furthermore, it is now known that mycoplasmas are just one instance of many of genome shrinkage in obligately host-associated bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Other examples are *Rickettsia*, *Buchnera aphidicola*, and *Borrelia burgdorferi*.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Small genome size in such species is associated with certain particularities, such as rapid evolution of polypeptide sequences and low GC content in the genome.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] The convergent evolution of these qualities in unrelated bacteria suggests that an obligate association with a host promotes genome reduction.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Given that over 80% of almost all of the fully sequenced bacterial genomes consist of intact ORFs, and that gene length is nearly constant at ~1 kb per gene, it is inferred that small genomes have few metabolic capabilities.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] While free-living bacteria, such as *E. coli*, *Salmonella* species, or *Bacillus* species, usually have 1500 to 6000 proteins encoded in their DNA, obligately pathogenic bacteria often have as few as 500 to 1000 such proteins.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] One candidate explanation is that reduced genomes maintain genes that are necessary for vital processes pertaining to cellular growth and replication, in addition to those genes that are required to survive in the bacteria's ecological niche.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] However, sequence data contradicts this hypothesis.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] The set of universal orthologs amongst eubacteria comprises only 15% of each genome.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Thus, each lineage has taken a different evolutionary path to reduced size.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Because universal cellular processes require over 80 genes, variation in genes imply that the same functions can be achieved by exploitation of nonhomologous genes.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Host-dependent bacteria are able to secure many compounds required for metabolism from the host's cytoplasm or tissue.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] They can, in turn, discard their own biosynthetic pathways and associated genes.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] This removal explains many of the specific gene losses.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] For example, the *Rickettsia* species, which relies on specific energy substrate from its host, has lost many of its native energy metabolism genes.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Similarly, most small genomes have lost their amino acid biosynthesizing genes, as these are found in the host instead.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] One exception is the *Buchnera*, an obligate maternally transmitted symbiont of aphids.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] It retains 54 genes for biosynthesis of crucial amino acids, but no longer has pathways for those amino acids that the host can synthesize.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Pathways for nucleotide biosynthesis are gone from many reduced genomes.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Those anabolic pathways that evolved through niche adaptation remain in particular genomes.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] The hypothesis that unused genes are eventually removed does not explain why many of the removed genes would indeed remain helpful in obligate pathogens.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] For example, many eliminated genes code for products that are involved in universal cellular processes, including replication, transcription, and translation.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Even genes supporting DNA recombination and repair are deleted from every small genome.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] However some genes, such as those encoding the RecA protein, were found to be nearly ubiquitous, indicating that a large majority of bacterial genomes are probably capable of homologous recombination.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] In addition, small genomes have fewer tRNAs, utilizing one for several amino acids.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] So, a single codon pairs with multiple codons, which likely yields less-than-optimal translation machinery.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] It is unknown why obligate intracellular pathogens would benefit by retaining fewer tRNAs and fewer DNA repair enzymes.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Another factor to consider is the change in population that corresponds to an evolution towards an obligately pathogenic life.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Such a shift in lifestyle often results in a reduction in the genetic population size of a lineage, since there is a finite number of hosts to occupy.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] This genetic drift may result in fixation of mutations that inactivate otherwise beneficial genes, or otherwise may decrease the efficiency of gene products.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Hence, not will only useless genes be lost (as mutations disrupt them once the bacteria has settled into host dependency), but also beneficial genes may be lost if genetic drift enforces ineffective purifying selection.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] The number of universally maintained genes is small and inadequate for independent cellular growth and replication, so that small genome species must achieve such feats by means of varying genes.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] This is done partly through nonorthologous gene displacement.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] That is, the role of one gene is replaced by another gene that achieves the same function.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Redundancy within the ancestral, larger genome is eliminated.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] The descendant small genome content depends on the content of chromosomal deletions that occur in the early stages of genome reduction.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] The very small genome of *M. genitalium* possesses dispensable genes.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] In a study in which single genes of this organism were inactivated using transposon-mediated mutagenesis, at least 129 of its 484 ORGs were not required for growth.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] A much smaller genome than that of the *M. genitalium* is therefore feasible.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] One theory predicts that bacteria have smaller genomes due to a selective pressure on genome size to ensure faster replication.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] The theory is based upon the logical premise that smaller bacterial genomes will take less time to replicate.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Subsequently, smaller genomes will be selected preferentially due to enhanced fitness.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] A study done by Mira et al. indicated little to no correlation between genome size and doubling time.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] The data indicates that selection is not a suitable explanation for the small sizes of bacterial genomes.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Still, many researchers believe there is some selective pressure on bacteria to maintain small genome size.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Selection is but one process involved in evolution.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Two other major processes (mutation and genetic drift) can account for the genome sizes of various types of bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] A study done by Mira et al. examined the size of insertions and deletions in bacterial pseudogenes.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Results indicated that mutational deletions tend to be larger than insertions in bacteria in the absence of gene transfer or gene duplication.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Insertions caused by horizontal or lateral gene transfer and gene duplication tend to involve transfer of large amounts of genetic material.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Assuming a lack of these processes, genomes will tend to reduce in size in the absence of selective constraint.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Evidence of a deletional bias is present in the respective genome sizes of free-living bacteria, facultative and recently derived parasites and obligate parasites and symbionts.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Free-living bacteria tend to have large population sizes and are subject to more opportunity for gene transfer.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] As such, selection can effectively operate on free-living bacteria to remove deleterious sequences resulting in a relatively small number of pseudogenes.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Continually, further selective pressure is evident as free-living bacteria must produce all gene-products independent of a host.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Given that there is sufficient opportunity for gene transfer to occur and there are selective pressures against even slightly deleterious deletions, it is intuitive that free-living bacteria should have the largest bacterial genomes of all bacteria types.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Recently formed parasites undergo severe bottlenecks and can rely on host environments to provide gene products.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] As such, in recently formed and facultative parasites, there is an accumulation of pseudogenes and transposable elements due to a lack of selective pressure against deletions.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] The population bottlenecks reduce gene transfer and as such, deletional bias ensures the reduction of genome size in parasitic bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Obligatory parasites and symbionts have the smallest genome sizes due to prolonged effects of deletional bias.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Parasites which have evolved to occupy specific niches are not exposed to much selective pressure.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] As such, genetic drift dominates the evolution of niche-specific bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Extended exposure to deletional bias ensures the removal of most superfluous sequences.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Symbionts occur in drastically lower numbers and undergo the most severe bottlenecks of any bacterial type.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] There is almost no opportunity for gene transfer for endosymbiotic bacteria, and thus genome compaction can be extreme.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] One of the smallest bacterial genomes ever to be sequenced is that of the endosymbiont *Carsonella rudii*.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] At 160 kbp, the genome of *Carsonella* is one of the most streamlined examples of a genome examined to date.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Molecular phylogenetics has revealed that every clade of bacteria with genome sizes under 2 Mb was derived from ancestors with much larger genomes, thus refuting the hypothesis that bacteria evolved by the successive doubling of small-genomed ancestors.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Recent studies performed by Nilsson et al. examined the rates of bacterial genome reduction of obligate bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Bacteria were cultured introducing frequent bottlenecks and growing cells in serial passage to reduce gene transfer so as to mimic conditions of endosymbiotic bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] The data predicted that bacteria exhibiting a one-day generation time lose as many as 1,000 kbp in as few as 50,000 years (a relatively short evolutionary time period).
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Furthermore, after deleting genes essential to the methyl-directed DNA mismatch repair (MMR) system, it was shown that bacterial genome size reduction increased in rate by as much as 50 times.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] These results indicate that genome size reduction can occur relatively rapidly, and loss of certain genes can speed up the process of bacterial genome compaction.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] This is not to suggest that all bacterial genomes are reducing in size and complexity.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] While many types of bacteria have reduced in genome size from an ancestral state, there are still a huge number of bacteria that maintained or increased genome size over ancestral states.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Free-living bacteria experience huge population sizes, fast generation times and a relatively high potential for gene transfer.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] While deletional bias tends to remove unnecessary sequences, selection can operate significantly amongst free-living bacteria resulting in evolution of new genes and processes.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Unlike eukaryotes, which evolve mainly through the modification of existing genetic information, bacteria have acquired a large percentage of their genetic diversity by the horizontal transfer of genes.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] This creates quite dynamic genomes, in which DNA can be introduced into and removed from the chromosome.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Bacteria have more variation in their metabolic properties, cellular structures, and lifestyles than can be accounted for by point mutations alone.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] For example, none of the phenotypic traits that distinguish *E. coli* from *Salmonella enterica* can be attributed to point mutation.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] On the contrary, evidence suggests that horizontal gene transfer has bolstered the diversification and speciation of many bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Horizontal gene transfer is often detected via DNA sequence information.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] DNA segments obtained by this mechanism often reveal a narrow phylogenetic distribution between related species.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Furthermore, these regions sometimes display an unexpected level of similarity to genes from taxa that are assumed to be quite divergent.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Although gene comparisons and phylogenetic studies are helpful in investigating horizontal gene transfer, the DNA sequences of genes are even more revelatory of their origin and ancestry within a genome.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Bacterial species differ widely in overall GC content, although the genes in any one species' genome are roughly identical with respect to base composition, patterns of codon usage, and frequencies of di- and trinucleotides.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] As a result, sequences that are newly acquired through lateral transfer can be identified via their characteristics, which remains that of the donor.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] For example, many of the *S. enterica* genes that are not present in *E. coli* have base compositions that differ from the overall 52% GC content of the entire chromosome.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Within this species, some lineages have more than a megabase of DNA that is not present in other lineages.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] The base compositions of these lineage-specific sequences imply that at least half of these sequences were captured through lateral transfer.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Furthermore, the regions adjacent to horizontally obtained genes often have remnants of translocatable elements, transfer origins of plasmids, or known attachment sites of phage integrases.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] In some species, a large proportion of laterally transferred genes originate from plasmid-, phage-, or transposon-related sequences.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Although sequence-based methods reveal the prevalence of horizontal gene transfer in bacteria, the results tend to be underestimates of the magnitude of this mechanism, since sequences obtained from donors whose sequence characteristics are similar to those of the recipient will avoid detection.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Comparisons of completely sequenced genomes confirm that bacterial chromosomes are amalgams of ancestral and laterally acquired sequences.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] The hyperthermophilic Eubacteria *Aquifex aeolicus* and *Thermotoga maritima* each has many genes that are similar in protein sequence to homologues in thermophilic Archaea.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] 24% of *Thermotoga's* 1,877 ORFs and 16% of *Aquifex's* 1,512 ORFs show high matches to an Archaeal protein, while mesophiles such as *E. coli* and *B. subtilis* have far lesser proportions of genes that are most like Archaeal homologues.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] The genesis of new abilities due to horizontal gene transfer has three requirements.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] First, there must exist a possible route for the donor DNA to be accepted by the recipient cell.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Additionally, the obtained sequence must be integrated with the rest of the genome.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Finally, these integrated genes must benefit the recipient bacterial organism.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] The first two steps can be achieved via three mechanisms: transformation, transduction and conjugation.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Transformation involves the uptake of named DNA from the environment.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Through transformation, DNA can be transmitted between distantly related organisms.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Some bacterial species, such as *Haemophilus influenzae* and *Neisseria gonorrhoeae*, are continuously competent to accept DNA.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Other species, such as *Bacillus subtilis* and *Streptococcus pneumoniae*, become competent when they enter a particular phase in their lifecycle.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Transformation in *N. gonorrhoeae* and *H. influenzae* is effective only if particular recognition sequences are found in the recipient genomes (5'-GCCGTCTGAA-3' and 5'-AAGTGCGGT-3'. respectively).
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Although the existence of certain uptake sequences improve transformation capability between related species, many of the inherently competent bacterial species, such as *B. subtilis* and *S. pneumoniae*, do not display sequence preference.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] New genes may be introduced into bacteria by a bacteriophage that has replicated within a donor through generalized transduction or specialized transduction.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] The amount of DNA that can be transmitted in one event is constrained by the size of the phage capsid (although the upper limit is about 100 kilobases).
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] While phages are numerous in the environment, the range of microorganisms that can be transduced depends on receptor recognition by the bacteriophage.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Transduction does not require both donor and recipient cells to be present simultaneously in time nor space.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Phage-encoded proteins both mediate the transfer of DNA into the recipient cytoplasm and assist integration of DNA into the chromosome.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Conjugation involves physical contact between donor and recipient cells and is able to mediate transfers of genes between domains, such as between bacteria and yeast.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] DNA is transmitted from donor to recipient either by self-transmissible or mobilizable plasmid.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Conjugation may mediate the transfer of chromosomal sequences by plasmids that integrate into the chromosome.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Despite the multitude of mechanisms mediating gene transfer among bacteria, the process's success is not guaranteed unless the received sequence is stably maintained in the recipient.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] DNA integration can be sustained through one of many processes.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] One is persistence as an episome, another is homologous recombination, and still another is illegitimate incorporation through lucky double-strand break repair.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Natural transformation is a DNA transfer process that depends on the expression of numerous bacterial genes.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] In order for a bacterium to bind, take up and recombine exogenous DNA into its chromosome, it must enter a special physiological state referred to as "competence".
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Competence development in the bacterium *Bacillus subtilis* requires expression of about 40 genes.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] In general, the DNA integrated into the host chromosome is (with rare exceptions) derived from another bacterium of the same species, and is therefore homologous to the resident chromosome.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] In *B. subtilis* the length of the transferred DNA is more than 1 million bases, is likely double stranded DNA, and is often more than a third of the total chromosome length of 4215 kb.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Approximately 7-9% of the recipient cells take up an entire chromosome.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] The capacity for natural transformation appears to be common among prokaryotes, and thus far 67 prokaryotic species (in seven different phyla) are known to undergo this process.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Competence for transformation is typically induced by high cell density and/or nutritional limitation, conditions associated with the stationary phase of bacterial growth.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Competence is also specifically induced by conditions that damage DNA.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] For example, transformation is induced in *Streptococcus pneumoniae* by the DNA damaging agents mitomycin C (a DNA cross-linking agent) and fluoroquinolone (a topoisomerase inhibitor that causes double-strand breaks).
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] In *Bacillus subtilis*, transformation is stimulated by exposure to UV light, a DNA damaging agent.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Of these toxic compounds, only six, all DNA damaging agents, caused strong induction.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Bacteria that are growing logarithmically differ from stationary phase bacteria with regard to the number of genome copies present in the cell, and this has implications for the ability to carry out an important DNA repair process.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] During logarithmic growth, two or more copies of any particular region of the chromosome are ordinarily present in a bacterial cell, as cell division is not precisely matched with chromosome replication.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Homologous recombinational repair is an important DNA repair process that is particularly effective for repairing double-strand damages, such as double-strand breaks.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] This DNA repair process depends on a second homologous chromosome in addition to the damaged chromosome.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] During logarithmic growth, a DNA damage in one chromosome may be removed by homologous recombinational repair using sequence information from the other homologous chromosome.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] However, when cells approach stationary phase they typically have just one copy of the chromosome, and homologous recombinational repair then requires input of an homologous template from outside the cell by transformation.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] The particular process likely responsible for repair was homologous recombinational repair.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Thus transformation in bacteria can be regarded as a primitive sexual process, in the sense that it involves interaction of homologous DNA from two individuals to form recombinant DNA that is then passed on to succeeding generations.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Antimicrobial resistance genes grant an organism the ability to grow its ecological niche, since it can now survive in the presence of previously lethal compounds.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] As the benefit to a bacterium earned from receiving such genes are time- and space-independent, those sequences that are highly mobile are selected for.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Plasmids are quite mobilizable between taxa and are the most frequent way by which bacteria acquire antibiotic resistance genes.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Adoption of a pathogenic lifestyle often yields a fundamental shift in an organism's ecological niche.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] The erratic phylogenetic distribution of pathogenic organisms implies that bacterial virulence is a consequence of the presence, or obtainment of, genes that are missing in avirulent forms.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] Evidence of this includes the discovery of large 'virulence' plasmids in pathogenic *Shigella* and *Yersinia*, as well as the ability to bestow pathogenic properties onto *E. coli* via experimental exposure to genes from other species.
[src:strain-biology/average-nucleotide-identity] In April 2019, scientists at ETH Zurich reported the creation of the world's first bacterial genome, named *Caulobacter ethensis-2.0*, made entirely by a computer, although a related viable form of *C. ethensis-2.0* does not yet exist.
[src:strain-biology/axenic] In biology, **axenic** (/eɪˈzɛnɪk/, /eɪˈzinɪk/) describes the state of a culture in which only a single species, variety, or strain of organism is present and entirely free of all other contaminating organisms.
[src:strain-biology/axenic] The earliest axenic cultures were of bacteria or unicellular eukaryotes, but axenic cultures of many multicellular organisms are also possible.
[src:strain-biology/axenic] Axenic culture is an important tool for the study of symbiotic and parasitic organisms in a controlled environment.
[src:strain-biology/axenic] Axenic cultures of microorganisms are typically prepared by subculture of an existing mixed culture.
[src:strain-biology/axenic] This may involve use of a dilution series, in which a culture is successively diluted to the point where subsamples of it contain only a few individual organisms, ideally only a single individual (in the case of an asexual species).
[src:strain-biology/axenic] These subcultures are allowed to grow until the identity of their constituent organisms can be ascertained.
[src:strain-biology/axenic] Selection of those cultures consisting solely of the desired organism produces the axenic culture.
[src:strain-biology/axenic] Subculture selection may also involve manually sampling the target organism from an uncontaminated growth front in an otherwise mixed culture, and using this as an inoculum source for the subculture.
[src:strain-biology/axenic] Axenic cultures are usually checked routinely to ensure that they remain axenic.
[src:strain-biology/axenic] One standard approach with microorganisms is to spread a sample of the culture onto an agar plate, and to incubate this for a fixed period of time.
[src:strain-biology/axenic] The agar should be an enriched medium that will support the growth of common "contaminating" organisms.
[src:strain-biology/axenic] Such "contaminating" organisms will grow on the plate during this period, identifying cultures that are no longer axenic.
[src:strain-biology/axenic] As axenic cultures are derived from very few organisms, or even a single individual, they are useful because the organisms present within them share a relatively narrow gene pool.
[src:strain-biology/axenic] In the case of an asexual species derived from a single individual, the resulting culture should consist of identical organisms (though processes such as mutation and horizontal gene transfer may introduce a degree of variability).
[src:strain-biology/axenic] Consequently, they will generally respond in a more uniform and reproducible fashion, simplifying the interpretation of experiments.
[src:strain-biology/axenic] The axenic culture of some pathogens is complicated because they normally thrive within host tissues which exhibit properties that are difficult to replicate *in vitro*.
[src:strain-biology/axenic] This is especially true in the case of intracellular pathogens.
[src:strain-biology/axenic] However, careful replication of key features of the host environment can resolve these difficulties (e.g. host metabolites, dissolved oxygen), such as with the Q fever pathogen, *Coxiella burnetii*.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Like all animals, humans carry vast numbers (approximately 1013 to 1014) of bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Most are in the gut, though there are many on the skin.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Most of the bacteria in and on the body are harmless or rendered so by the protective effects of the immune system, and many are beneficial, particularly the ones in the gut.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] However, several species of bacteria are pathogenic and cause infectious diseases, including cholera, syphilis, anthrax, leprosy, tuberculosis, tetanus and bubonic plague.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The most common fatal bacterial diseases are respiratory infections.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Antibiotics are used to treat bacterial infections and are also used in farming, making antibiotic resistance a growing problem.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Once regarded as plants constituting the class *Schizomycetes* ("fission fungi"), bacteria are now classified as prokaryotes.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Unlike cells of animals and other eukaryotes, bacterial cells contain circular chromosomes, do not contain a nucleus and rarely harbour membrane-bound organelles.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Although the term *bacteria* traditionally included all prokaryotes, the scientific classification changed after the discovery in the 1990s that prokaryotes consist of two very different groups of organisms that evolved from an ancient common ancestor.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] These evolutionary domains are called Bacteria and Archaea.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Unlike Archaea, bacteria contain ester-linked lipids in the cell membrane, possess elongation factors that are resistant to ADP-ribosylation by diphtheria toxin, use formylmethionine in protein synthesis initiation, and have numerous genetic differences, including a different 16S rRNA.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The word was first used to refer to bacteria in 1828.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Although an estimated 43,000 species of bacteria have been named, most of them have never been studied.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] In fact, just 10 bacterial species account for half of all publications, whereas nearly 75% of all named bacteria have no academic research devoted to them.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The best-studied species, *Escherichia coli*, has more than 300,000 studies published on it, but many of these papers likely use it only as a cloning vehicle to study other species, without providing any insight into its own biology.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] 90% of scientific studies on bacteria focus on less than 1% of species, mostly pathogenic bacteria relevant to human health.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] While *E. coli* is probably the best-studied bacterium, a quarter of its 4000 genes are poorly studied or remain uncharacterized.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria with minimal genomes (< 600 genes, e.g.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] *Mycoplasma*) usually have a large fraction of their genes functionally characterized, given that most of them are essential and conserved in many other species.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The ancestors of bacteria were unicellular microorganisms that were the first forms of life to appear on Earth, about 4 billion years ago.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] For about 3 billion years, most organisms were microscopic, and bacteria and archaea were the dominant forms of life.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Although bacterial fossils exist, such as stromatolites, their lack of distinctive morphology prevents them from being used to examine the history of bacterial evolution, or to date the time of origin of a particular bacterial species.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] However, gene sequences can be used to reconstruct the bacterial phylogeny, and these studies indicate that bacteria diverged first from the archaeal/eukaryotic lineage.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The most recent common ancestor (MRCA) of bacteria and archaea was probably a hyperthermophile that lived about 2.5 billion–3.2 billion years ago.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The earliest life on land may have been bacteria some 3.22 billion years ago.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria were also involved in the second great evolutionary divergence, that of the archaea and eukaryotes.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Here, eukaryotes resulted from the entering of ancient bacteria into endosymbiotic associations with the ancestors of eukaryotic cells, which were themselves possibly related to the Archaea.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] This involved the engulfment by proto-eukaryotic cells of alphaproteobacterial symbionts to form either mitochondria or hydrogenosomes, which are still found in all known Eukarya (sometimes in highly reduced form, e.g. in species of amitochondrial protozoa).
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Later, some eukaryotes that already contained mitochondria also engulfed cyanobacteria-like organisms, leading to the formation of chloroplasts in algae and plants.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria are ubiquitous, living in every possible habitat on the planet including soil, underwater, deep in Earth's crust and even such extreme environments as acidic hot springs and radioactive waste.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] There are thought to be approximately 2×1030 bacteria on Earth, forming a biomass that is only exceeded by plants.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] They are abundant in lakes and oceans, in arctic ice, and geothermal springs where they provide the nutrients needed to sustain life by converting dissolved compounds, such as hydrogen sulphide and methane, to energy.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Most do not cause diseases, are beneficial to their environments, and are essential for life.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The soil is a rich source of bacteria and a few grams contain around a thousand million of them.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] They are all essential to soil ecology, breaking down toxic waste and recycling nutrients.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] They are even found in the atmosphere and one cubic metre of air holds around one hundred million bacterial cells.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The oceans and seas harbour around 3 × 1026 bacteria which provide up to 50% of the oxygen humans breathe.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Only around 2% of bacterial species have been fully studied.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria display a wide diversity of shapes and sizes.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cells are about one-tenth the size of eukaryotic cells and are typically 0.5–5.0 micrometres in length.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] However, a few species are visible to the unaided eye—for example, *Thiomargarita namibiensis* is up to half a millimetre long, *Epulopiscium fishelsoni* reaches 0.7 mm, and *Thiomargarita magnifica* can reach even 2 cm in length, which is 50 times larger than other known bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Among the smallest bacteria are members of the genus *Mycoplasma*, which measure only 0.3 micrometres, as small as the largest viruses.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria may be even smaller, but these ultramicrobacteria are not well-studied.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Most bacterial species are either spherical, called *cocci* (*singular coccus*, from Greek *kókkos*, grain, seed), or rod-shaped, called *bacilli* (*sing*. bacillus, from Latin *baculus*, stick).
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria, called *vibrio*, are shaped like slightly curved rods or comma-shaped; others can be spiral-shaped, called *spirilla*, or tightly coiled, called *spirochaetes*.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] A small number of other unusual shapes have been described, such as star-shaped bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] This wide variety of shapes is determined by the bacterial cell wall and cytoskeleton and is important because it can influence the ability of bacteria to acquire nutrients, attach to surfaces, swim through liquids and escape predators.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Most bacterial species exist as single cells; others associate in characteristic patterns: *Neisseria* forms diploids (pairs), streptococci form chains, and staphylococci group together in "bunch of grapes" clusters.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can also group to form larger multicellular structures, such as the elongated filaments of *Actinomycetota* species, the aggregates of *Myxobacteria* species, and the complex hyphae of *Streptomyces* species.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] These multicellular structures are often only seen in certain conditions.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] For example, when starved of amino acids, myxobacteria detect surrounding cells in a process known as quorum sensing, migrate towards each other, and aggregate to form fruiting bodies up to 500 micrometres long and containing approximately 100,000 bacterial cells.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] In these fruiting bodies, the bacteria perform separate tasks; for example, about one in ten cells migrate to the top of a fruiting body and differentiate into a specialised dormant state called a myxospore, which is more resistant to drying and other adverse environmental conditions.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria often attach to surfaces and form dense aggregations called biofilms and larger formations known as microbial mats.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] These biofilms and mats can range from a few micrometres in thickness to up to half a metre in depth, and may contain multiple species of bacteria, protists and archaea.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria living in biofilms display a complex arrangement of cells and extracellular components, forming secondary structures, such as microcolonies, through which there are networks of channels to enable better diffusion of nutrients.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] In natural environments, such as soil or the surfaces of plants, the majority of bacteria are bound to surfaces in biofilms.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Biofilms are also important in medicine, as these structures are often present during chronic bacterial infections or in infections of implanted medical devices, and bacteria protected within biofilms are much harder to kill than individual isolated bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The bacterial cell is surrounded by a cell membrane, which is made primarily of phospholipids.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] This membrane encloses the contents of the cell and acts as a barrier to hold nutrients, proteins and other essential components within the cell.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Unlike eukaryotic cells, bacteria usually lack large membrane-bound structures in their cytoplasm such as a nucleus, mitochondria, chloroplasts and the other organelles present in eukaryotic cells.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] However, some bacteria have protein-bound organelles in the cytoplasm which compartmentalise aspects of bacterial metabolism, such as the carboxysome.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Additionally, bacteria have a multi-component cytoskeleton to control the localisation of proteins and nucleic acids within the cell, and to manage the process of cell division.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Many important biochemical reactions, such as energy generation, occur due to differences in concentration of molecules across membranes, creating a electrochemical potential analogous to a battery.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The general lack of internal membranes in bacteria means these reactions, such as electron transport, occur across the cell membrane between the cytoplasm and the outside of the cell or periplasm.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] However, in many photosynthetic bacteria, the plasma membrane is highly folded and fills most of the cell with layers of light-gathering membrane.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] These light-gathering complexes may even form lipid-enclosed structures called chlorosomes in green sulfur bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria do not have a membrane-bound nucleus, and their genetic material is typically a single circular bacterial chromosome of DNA located in the cytoplasm in an irregularly shaped body called the nucleoid.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The nucleoid contains the chromosome with its associated proteins and RNA.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Like all other organisms, bacteria contain ribosomes for the production of proteins, but the structure of the bacterial ribosome is different from that of eukaryotes and archaea.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Its translation process is also different.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria produce intracellular nutrient storage granules, such as glycogen, polyphosphate, sulfur or polyhydroxyalkanoates.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria such as the photosynthetic cyanobacteria, produce internal gas vacuoles, which they use to regulate their buoyancy, allowing them to move up or down into water layers with different light intensities and nutrient levels.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Around the outside of the cell membrane is the cell wall.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cell walls are made of peptidoglycan (also called murein), which is made from polysaccharide chains cross-linked by peptides containing D-amino acids.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Bacterial cell walls are different from the cell walls of plants and fungi, which are made of cellulose and chitin, respectively.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The cell wall of bacteria is also distinct from that of archaea, which do not contain peptidoglycan.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The cell wall is essential to the survival of many bacteria, and the antibiotic penicillin (produced by a fungus called *Penicillium*) is able to kill bacteria by inhibiting a step in the synthesis of peptidoglycan.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] There are broadly speaking two different types of cell wall in bacteria, that classify bacteria into Gram-positive bacteria and Gram-negative bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The names originate from the reaction of cells to the Gram stain, a long-standing test for the classification of bacterial species.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Gram-positive bacteria possess a thick cell wall containing many layers of peptidoglycan and teichoic acids.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] In contrast, Gram-negative bacteria have a relatively thin cell wall consisting of a few layers of peptidoglycan surrounded by a second lipid membrane containing lipopolysaccharides and lipoproteins.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Most bacteria have the Gram-negative cell wall, and only members of the *Bacillota* group and actinomycetota (previously known as the low G+C and high G+C Gram-positive bacteria, respectively) have the alternative Gram-positive arrangement.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] These differences in structure can produce differences in antibiotic susceptibility; for instance, vancomycin can kill only Gram-positive bacteria and is ineffective against Gram-negative pathogens, such as *Haemophilus influenzae* or *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria have cell wall structures that are neither classically Gram-positive or Gram-negative.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] This includes clinically important bacteria such as mycobacteria which have a thick peptidoglycan cell wall like a Gram-positive bacterium, but also a second outer layer of lipids.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] In many bacteria, an S-layer of rigidly arrayed protein molecules covers the outside of the cell.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] This layer provides chemical and physical protection for the cell surface and can act as a macromolecular diffusion barrier.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] S-layers have diverse functions and are known to act as virulence factors in *Campylobacter* species and contain surface enzymes in *Bacillus stearothermophilus*.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Flagella are rigid protein structures, about 20 nanometres in diameter and up to 20 micrometres in length, that are used for motility.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Flagella are driven by the energy released by the transfer of ions down an electrochemical gradient across the cell membrane.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Fimbriae (sometimes called "attachment pili") are fine filaments of protein, usually 2–10 nanometres in diameter and up to several micrometres in length.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] They are distributed over the surface of the cell, and resemble fine hairs when seen under the electron microscope.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Fimbriae are believed to be involved in attachment to solid surfaces or to other cells, and are essential for the virulence of some bacterial pathogens.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Pili (*sing*. pilus) are cellular appendages, slightly larger than fimbriae, that can transfer genetic material between bacterial cells in a process called conjugation where they are called conjugation pili or sex pili (see bacterial genetics, below).
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] They can also generate movement where they are called type IV pili.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Glycocalyx is produced by many bacteria to surround their cells, and varies in structural complexity: ranging from a disorganised slime layer of extracellular polymeric substances to a highly structured capsule.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] These structures can protect cells from engulfment by eukaryotic cells such as macrophages (part of the human immune system).
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] They can also act as antigens and be involved in cell recognition, as well as aiding attachment to surfaces and the formation of biofilms.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The assembly of these extracellular structures is dependent on bacterial secretion systems.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] These transfer proteins from the cytoplasm into the periplasm or into the environment around the cell.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Many types of secretion systems are known and these structures are often essential for the virulence of pathogens, so are intensively studied.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Some genera of Gram-positive bacteria, such as *Bacillus*, *Clostridium*, *Sporohalobacter*, *Anaerobacter*, and *Heliobacterium*, can form highly resistant, dormant structures called *endospores*.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Endospores develop within the cytoplasm of the cell; generally, a single endospore develops in each cell.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Each endospore contains a core of DNA and ribosomes surrounded by a cortex layer and protected by a multilayer rigid coat composed of peptidoglycan and a variety of proteins.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Endospores show no detectable metabolism and can survive extreme physical and chemical stresses, such as high levels of UV light, gamma radiation, detergents, disinfectants, heat, freezing, pressure, and desiccation.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] In this dormant state, these organisms may remain viable for millions of years.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Endospores even allow bacteria to survive exposure to the vacuum and radiation of outer space, leading to the possibility that bacteria could be distributed throughout the universe by space dust, meteoroids, asteroids, comets, planetoids, or directed panspermia.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] *Clostridioides difficile* infection, a common problem in healthcare settings, is caused by spore-forming bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria exhibit an extremely wide variety of metabolic types.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The distribution of metabolic traits within a group of bacteria has traditionally been used to define their taxonomy, but these traits often do not correspond with modern genetic classifications.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Bacterial metabolism is classified into nutritional groups on the basis of three major criteria: the source of energy, the electron donors used, and the source of carbon used for growth.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Phototrophic bacteria derive energy from light using photosynthesis, while chemotrophic bacteria breaking down chemical compounds through oxidation, driving metabolism by transferring electrons from a given electron donor to a terminal electron acceptor in a redox reaction.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Chemotrophs are further divided by the types of compounds they use to transfer electrons.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria that derive electrons from inorganic compounds such as hydrogen, carbon monoxide, or ammonia are called lithotrophs, while those that use organic compounds are called organotrophs.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Still, more specifically, aerobic organisms use oxygen as the terminal electron acceptor, while anaerobic organisms use other compounds such as nitrate, sulfate, or carbon dioxide.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria, called heterotrophs, derive their carbon from other organic carbon.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Others, such as cyanobacteria and some purple bacteria, are autotrophic, meaning they obtain cellular carbon by fixing carbon dioxide.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] In unusual circumstances, the gas methane can be used by methanotrophic bacteria as both a source of electrons and a substrate for carbon anabolism.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] In many ways, bacterial metabolism provides traits that are useful for ecological stability and for human society.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] For example, diazotrophs have the ability to fix nitrogen gas using the enzyme nitrogenase.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] This trait, which can be found in bacteria of most metabolic types listed above, leads to the ecologically important processes of denitrification, sulfate reduction, and acetogenesis, respectively.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Bacterial metabolic processes are important drivers in biological responses to pollution; for example, sulfate-reducing bacteria are largely responsible for the production of the highly toxic forms of mercury (methyl- and dimethylmercury) in the environment.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Nonrespiratory anaerobes use fermentation to generate energy and reducing power, secreting metabolic by-products (such as ethanol in brewing) as waste.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Facultative anaerobes can switch between fermentation and different terminal electron acceptors depending on the environmental conditions in which they find themselves.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Unlike in multicellular organisms, increases in cell size (cell growth) and reproduction by cell division are tightly linked in unicellular organisms.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria grow to a fixed size and then reproduce through binary fission, a form of asexual reproduction.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Under optimal conditions, bacteria can grow and divide extremely rapidly, and some bacterial populations can double as quickly as every 17 minutes.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] In cell division, two identical clone daughter cells are produced.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria, while still reproducing asexually, form more complex reproductive structures that help disperse the newly formed daughter cells.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Examples include fruiting body formation by myxobacteria and aerial hyphae formation by *Streptomyces* species, or budding.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Budding involves a cell forming a protrusion that breaks away and produces a daughter cell.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] In the laboratory, bacteria are usually grown using solid or liquid media.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Solid growth media, such as agar plates, are used to isolate pure cultures of a bacterial strain.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] However, liquid growth media are used when the measurement of growth or large volumes of cells are required.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Growth in stirred liquid media occurs as an even cell suspension, making the cultures easy to divide and transfer, although isolating single bacteria from liquid media is difficult.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The use of selective media (media with specific nutrients added or deficient, or with antibiotics added) can help identify specific organisms.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Most laboratory techniques for growing bacteria use high levels of nutrients to produce large amounts of cells cheaply and quickly.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] However, in natural environments, nutrients are limited, meaning that bacteria cannot continue to reproduce indefinitely.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] This nutrient limitation has led the evolution of different growth strategies (see r/K selection theory).
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Some organisms can grow extremely rapidly when nutrients become available, such as the formation of algal and cyanobacterial blooms that often occur in lakes during the summer.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Other organisms have adaptations to harsh environments, such as the production of multiple antibiotics by *Streptomyces* that inhibit the growth of competing microorganisms.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] In nature, many organisms live in communities (e.g., biofilms) that may allow for increased supply of nutrients and protection from environmental stresses.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] These relationships can be essential for growth of a particular organism or group of organisms (syntrophy).
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] When a population of bacteria first enter a high-nutrient environment that allows growth, the cells need to adapt to their new environment.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The first phase of growth is the lag phase, a period of slow growth when the cells are adapting to the high-nutrient environment and preparing for fast growth.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The lag phase has high biosynthesis rates, as proteins necessary for rapid growth are produced.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The second phase of growth is the logarithmic phase, also known as the exponential phase.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The log phase is marked by rapid exponential growth.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The rate at which cells grow during this phase is known as the *growth rate* (*k*), and the time it takes the cells to double is known as the *generation time* (*g*).
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] During log phase, nutrients are metabolised at maximum speed until one of the nutrients is depleted and starts limiting growth.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The third phase of growth is the *stationary phase* and is caused by depleted nutrients.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The cells reduce their metabolic activity and consume non-essential cellular proteins.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The stationary phase is a transition from rapid growth to a stress response state and there is increased expression of genes involved in DNA repair, antioxidant metabolism and nutrient transport.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The final phase is the death phase where the bacteria run out of nutrients and die.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] There are many exceptions to this; for example, some *Streptomyces* and *Borrelia* species contain a single linear chromosome, while some bacteria including species of *Vibrio* contain more than one chromosome.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria contain plasmids, small extra-chromosomal molecules of DNA that may contain genes for various useful functions such as antibiotic resistance, metabolic capabilities, or various virulence factors.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Whether they have a single chromosome or more than one, almost all bacteria have a haploid genome.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] This means that they have only one copy of each gene encoding proteins.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] This is in contrast to eukaryotes, which are diploid or polyploid, meaning they have two or more copies of each gene.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] This means that unlike humans, who may still be able to create a protein if the gene becomes mutated (since the human genome has an extra copy in each cell), a bacterium will be completely unable to create the protein if its gene incurs an inactivating mutation.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Bacterial genomes usually encode a few hundred to a few thousand genes.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The genes in bacterial genomes are usually a single continuous stretch of DNA.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Although several different types of introns do exist in bacteria, these are much rarer than in eukaryotes.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria, as asexual organisms, inherit an identical copy of the parent's genome and are clonal.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] However, all bacteria can evolve by selection on changes to their genetic material DNA caused by genetic recombination or mutations.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Mutations arise from errors made during the replication of DNA or from exposure to mutagens.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Mutation rates vary widely among different species of bacteria and even among different clones of a single species of bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Genetic changes in bacterial genomes emerge from either random mutation during replication or "stress-directed mutation", where genes involved in a particular growth-limiting process have an increased mutation rate.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Some bacteria transfer genetic material between cells.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] First, bacteria can take up exogenous DNA from their environment in a process called transformation.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria can naturally take up DNA from the environment, while others must be chemically altered in order to induce them to take up DNA.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The development of competence in nature is usually associated with stressful environmental conditions and seems to be an adaptation for facilitating repair of DNA damage in recipient cells.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Second, bacteriophages can integrate into the bacterial chromosome, introducing foreign DNA in a process known as transduction.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Many types of bacteriophage exist; some infect and lyse their host bacteria, while others insert into the bacterial chromosome.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Third, bacteria can transfer genetic material through direct cell contact via conjugation.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] In such cases, gene acquisition from other bacteria or the environment is called horizontal gene transfer and may be common under natural conditions.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria are motile (able to move themselves) and do so using a variety of mechanisms.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The best studied of these are flagella, long filaments that are turned by a motor at the base to generate propeller-like movement.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The bacterial flagellum is made of about 20 proteins, with approximately another 30 proteins required for its regulation and assembly.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The flagellum is a rotating structure driven by a reversible motor at the base that uses the electrochemical gradient across the membrane for power.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can use flagella in different ways to generate different kinds of movement.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Many bacteria (such as *E. coli*) have two distinct modes of movement: forward movement (swimming) and tumbling.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The tumbling allows them to reorient and makes their movement a three-dimensional random walk.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The flagella of a group of bacteria, the spirochaetes, are found between two membranes in the periplasmic space.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] They have a distinctive helical body that twists about as it moves.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Two other types of bacterial motion are called twitching motility that relies on a structure called the type IV pilus, and gliding motility, that uses other mechanisms.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] In twitching motility, the rod-like pilus extends out from the cell, binds some substrate, and then retracts, pulling the cell forward.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Motile bacteria are attracted or repelled by certain stimuli in behaviours called *taxes*: these include chemotaxis, phototaxis, energy taxis, and magnetotaxis.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] In one peculiar group, the myxobacteria, individual bacteria move together to form waves of cells that then differentiate to form fruiting bodies containing spores.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The myxobacteria move only when on solid surfaces, unlike *E. coli*, which is motile in liquid or solid media.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Several *Listeria* and *Shigella* species move inside host cells by usurping the cytoskeleton, which is normally used to move organelles inside the cell.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] By promoting actin polymerisation at one pole of their cells, they can form a kind of tail that pushes them through the host cell's cytoplasm.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] A few bacteria have chemical systems that generate light.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] This bioluminescence often occurs in bacteria that live in association with fish, and the light probably serves to attract fish or other large animals.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria often function as multicellular aggregates known as biofilms, exchanging a variety of molecular signals for intercell communication and engaging in coordinated multicellular behaviour.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The communal benefits of multicellular cooperation include a cellular division of labour, accessing resources that cannot effectively be used by single cells, collectively defending against antagonists, and optimising population survival by differentiating into distinct cell types.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] For example, bacteria in biofilms can have more than five hundred times the increased resistance to antibacterial agents than individual "planktonic" bacteria of the same species.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] One type of intercellular communication by a molecular signal is called quorum sensing.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Quorum sensing determines whether the local population is dense enough to support investment in processes that are only successful if large numbers of similar organisms behave similarly, such as excreting digestive enzymes or emitting light.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Quorum sensing enables bacteria to coordinate gene expression and to produce, release, and detect autoinducers or pheromones that accumulate with the growth in cell population.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Classification seeks to describe the diversity of bacterial species by naming and grouping organisms based on similarities.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Bacteria can be classified on the basis of cell structure, cellular metabolism or on differences in cell components, such as DNA, fatty acids, pigments, antigens and quinones.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] While these schemes allowed the identification and classification of **bacterial strains**, it was unclear whether these differences represented variation between distinct species or between strains of the same species.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] This uncertainty was due to the lack of distinctive structures in most bacteria, as well as lateral gene transfer between unrelated species.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Due to lateral gene transfer, some closely related bacteria can have very different morphologies and metabolisms.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Classification of bacteria is determined by publication in the International Journal of Systematic Bacteriology, and Bergey's Manual of Systematic Bacteriology.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The International Committee on Systematic Bacteriology (ICSB) maintains international rules for the naming of bacteria and taxonomic categories and for the ranking of them in the International Code of Nomenclature of Bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Historically, bacteria were considered a part of the Plantae, the plant kingdom, and were called "Schizomycetes" (fission-fungi).
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] For this reason, collective bacteria and other microorganisms in a host are often called "flora".
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The term "bacteria" was traditionally applied to all microscopic, single-cell prokaryotes.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] However, molecular systematics showed prokaryotic life to consist of two separate domains, originally called Eubacteria and Archaebacteria, but now called Bacteria and Archaea that evolved independently from an ancient common ancestor.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The archaea and eukaryotes are more closely related to each other than either is to the bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] These two domains, along with Eukarya, are the basis of the three-domain system, which is currently the most widely used classification system in microbiology.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] However, due to the relatively recent introduction of molecular systematics and a rapid increase in the number of genome sequences that are available, bacterial classification remains a changing and expanding field.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] For example, Cavalier-Smith argued that the Archaea and Eukaryotes evolved from Gram-positive bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The identification of bacteria in the laboratory is particularly relevant in medicine, where the correct treatment is determined by the bacterial species causing an infection.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Consequently, the need to identify human pathogens was a major impetus for the development of techniques to identify bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Once a pathogenic organism has been isolated, it can be further characterised by its morphology, growth patterns (such as aerobic or anaerobic growth), patterns of hemolysis, and staining.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The *Gram stain*, developed in 1884 by Hans Christian Gram, characterises bacteria based on the structural characteristics of their cell walls.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The thick layers of peptidoglycan in the "Gram-positive" cell wall stain purple, while the thin "Gram-negative" cell wall appears pink.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] By combining morphology and Gram-staining, most bacteria can be classified as belonging to one of four groups (Gram-positive cocci, Gram-positive bacilli, Gram-negative cocci and Gram-negative bacilli).
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Some organisms are best identified by stains other than the Gram stain, particularly mycobacteria or *Nocardia*, which show acid fastness on Ziehl–Neelsen or similar stains.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Culture techniques are designed to promote the growth and identify particular bacteria while restricting the growth of the other bacteria in the sample.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Often these techniques are designed for specific specimens; for example, a sputum sample will be treated to identify organisms that cause pneumonia, while stool specimens are cultured on selective media to identify organisms that cause diarrhea while preventing growth of non-pathogenic bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Specimens that are normally sterile, such as blood, urine or spinal fluid, are cultured under conditions designed to grow all possible organisms.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Other organisms may need to be identified by their growth in special media, or by other techniques, such as serology.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] As with bacterial classification, identification of bacteria is increasingly using molecular methods, and mass spectroscopy.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Most bacteria have not been characterised and there are many species that cannot be grown in the laboratory.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Diagnostics using DNA-based tools, such as polymerase chain reaction, are increasingly popular due to their specificity and speed, compared to culture-based methods.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] These methods also allow the detection and identification of "viable but nonculturable" cells that are metabolically active but non-dividing.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] The main way to characterize and classify these bacteria is to isolate their DNA from environmental samples and mass-sequence them.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] This approach has identified thousands, if not millions of candidate species.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p01] Based on some estimates, more than 43,000 species of bacteria have been described, but attempts to estimate the true number of bacterial diversity have ranged from 107 to 109 total species—and even these diverse estimates may be off by many orders of magnitude.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Despite their apparent simplicity, bacteria can form complex associations with other organisms.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] These symbiotic associations can be divided into parasitism, mutualism and commensalism.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] The word "commensalism" is derived from the word "commensal", meaning "eating at the same table" and all plants and animals are colonised by commensal bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] In humans and other animals, trillions of them live on the skin, the airways, the gut and other orifices.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Referred to as "normal flora", or "commensals", these bacteria usually cause no harm but may occasionally invade other sites of the body and cause infection.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] *Escherichia coli* is a commensal in the human gut but can cause urinary tract infections.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Similarly, streptococci, which are part of the normal flora of the human mouth, can cause heart disease.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Some species of bacteria kill and then consume other microorganisms; these species are called *predatory bacteria*.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] These include organisms such as *Myxococcus xanthus*, which forms swarms of cells that kill and digest any bacteria they encounter.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Other bacterial predators either attach to their prey in order to digest them and absorb nutrients or invade another cell and multiply inside the cytosol.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] These predatory bacteria are thought to have evolved from saprophages that consumed dead microorganisms, through adaptations that allowed them to entrap and kill other organisms.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Certain bacteria form close spatial associations that are essential for their survival.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] One such mutualistic association, called interspecies hydrogen transfer, occurs between clusters of anaerobic bacteria that consume organic acids, such as butyric acid or propionic acid, and produce hydrogen, and methanogenic archaea that consume hydrogen.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] The bacteria in this association are unable to consume the organic acids as this reaction produces hydrogen that accumulates in their surroundings.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Only the intimate association with the hydrogen-consuming archaea keeps the hydrogen concentration low enough to allow the bacteria to grow.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] In soil, microorganisms that reside in the rhizosphere (a zone that includes the root surface and the soil that adheres to the root after gentle shaking) carry out nitrogen fixation, converting nitrogen gas to nitrogenous compounds.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] This serves to provide an easily absorbable form of nitrogen for many plants, which cannot fix nitrogen themselves.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Many other bacteria are found as symbionts in humans and other organisms.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] The presence of this gut flora also inhibits the growth of potentially pathogenic bacteria (usually through competitive exclusion) and these beneficial bacteria are consequently sold as probiotic dietary supplements.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Nearly all animal life is dependent on bacteria for survival as only bacteria and some archaea possess the genes and enzymes necessary to synthesise vitamin B12, also known as cobalamin, and provide it through the food chain.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Vitamin B12 is a water-soluble vitamin that is involved in the metabolism of every cell of the human body.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] It is a cofactor in DNA synthesis and in both fatty acid and amino acid metabolism.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] It is particularly important in the normal functioning of the nervous system via its role in the synthesis of myelin.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] The body is continually exposed to many species of bacteria, including beneficial commensals, which grow on the skin and mucous membranes, and saprophytes, which grow mainly in the soil and in decaying matter.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] The blood and tissue fluids contain nutrients sufficient to sustain the growth of many bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] The body has defence mechanisms that enable it to resist microbial invasion of its tissues and give it a natural immunity or innate resistance against many microorganisms.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Unlike some viruses, bacteria evolve relatively slowly so many bacterial diseases also occur in other animals.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] If bacteria form a parasitic association with other organisms, they are classed as pathogens.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] A pathogenic cause for a known medical disease may only be discovered many years later, as was the case with *Helicobacter pylori* and peptic ulcer disease.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Bacterial diseases are also important in agriculture, and bacteria cause leaf spot, fire blight and wilts in plants, as well as Johne's disease, mastitis, salmonella and anthrax in farm animals.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Each species of pathogen has a characteristic spectrum of interactions with its human hosts.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Some organisms, such as *Staphylococcus* or *Streptococcus*, can cause skin infections, pneumonia, meningitis and sepsis, a systemic inflammatory response producing shock, massive vasodilation and death.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Yet these organisms are also part of the normal human flora and usually exist on the skin or in the nose without causing any disease at all.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Other organisms invariably cause disease in humans, such as *Rickettsia*, which are obligate intracellular parasites able to grow and reproduce only within the cells of other organisms.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] One species of *Rickettsia* causes typhus, while another causes Rocky Mountain spotted fever.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] *Chlamydia*, another phylum of obligate intracellular parasites, contains species that can cause pneumonia or urinary tract infection and may be involved in coronary heart disease.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Some species, such as *Pseudomonas aeruginosa*, *Burkholderia cenocepacia*, and *Mycobacterium avium*, are opportunistic pathogens and cause disease mainly in people who are immunosuppressed or have cystic fibrosis.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Some bacteria produce toxins, which cause diseases.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] These are endotoxins, which come from broken bacterial cells, and exotoxins, which are produced by bacteria and released into the environment.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] The bacterium *Clostridium botulinum* for example, produces a powerful exotoxin that cause respiratory paralysis, and *Salmonellae* produce an endotoxin that causes gastroenteritis.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Some exotoxins can be converted to toxoids, which are used as vaccines to prevent the disease.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Bacterial infections may be treated with antibiotics, which are classified as bacteriocidal if they kill bacteria or bacteriostatic if they just prevent bacterial growth.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] There are many types of antibiotics, and each class inhibits a process that is different in the pathogen from that found in the host.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] An example of how antibiotics produce selective toxicity are chloramphenicol and puromycin, which inhibit the bacterial ribosome, but not the structurally different eukaryotic ribosome.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Antibiotics are used both in treating human disease and in intensive farming to promote animal growth, where they may be contributing to the rapid development of antibiotic resistance in bacterial populations.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Infections can be prevented by antiseptic measures such as sterilising the skin prior to piercing it with the needle of a syringe, and by proper care of indwelling catheters.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Surgical and dental instruments are also sterilised to prevent contamination by bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Disinfectants such as bleach are used to kill bacteria or other pathogens on surfaces to prevent contamination and further reduce the risk of infection.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Bacteria, often lactic acid bacteria, such as *Lactobacillus* species and *Lactococcus* species, in combination with yeasts and moulds, have been used for thousands of years in the preparation of fermented foods, such as cheese, pickles, soy sauce, sauerkraut, vinegar, wine, and yogurt.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] The ability of bacteria to degrade a variety of organic compounds is remarkable and has been used in waste processing and bioremediation.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Bacteria capable of digesting the hydrocarbons in petroleum are often used to clean up oil spills.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Fertiliser was added to some of the beaches in Prince William Sound in an attempt to promote the growth of these naturally occurring bacteria after the 1989 *Exxon Valdez* oil spill.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] These efforts were effective on beaches that were not too thickly covered in oil.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Bacteria are also used for the bioremediation of industrial toxic wastes.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] In the chemical industry, bacteria are most important in the production of enantiomerically pure chemicals for use as pharmaceuticals or agrichemicals.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Bacteria can also be used in place of pesticides in biological pest control.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] This commonly involves *Bacillus thuringiensis* (also called BT), a Gram-positive, soil-dwelling bacterium.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Subspecies of this bacteria are used as Lepidopteran-specific insecticides under trade names such as Dipel and Thuricide.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Because of their specificity, these pesticides are regarded as environmentally friendly, with little or no effect on humans, wildlife, pollinators, and most other beneficial insects.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Because of their ability to quickly grow and the relative ease with which they can be manipulated, bacteria are the workhorses for the fields of molecular biology, genetics, and biochemistry.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] By making mutations in bacterial DNA and examining the resulting phenotypes, scientists can determine the function of genes, enzymes, and metabolic pathways in bacteria, then apply this knowledge to more complex organisms.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] This aim of understanding the biochemistry of a cell reaches its most complex expression in the synthesis of huge amounts of enzyme kinetic and gene expression data into mathematical models of entire organisms.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] This is achievable in some well-studied bacteria, with models of *Escherichia coli* metabolism now being produced and tested.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] This understanding of bacterial metabolism and genetics allows the use of biotechnology to bioengineer bacteria for the production of therapeutic proteins, such as insulin, growth factors, or antibodies.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Because of their importance for research in general, samples of bacterial strains are isolated and preserved in Biological Resource Centres.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] This ensures the availability of the strain to scientists worldwide.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Bacteria were first observed by the Dutch microscopist Antonie van Leeuwenhoek in 1676, using a single-lens microscope of his own design.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Leeuwenhoek did not recognize bacteria as a distinct category of microorganisms, referring to all microorganisms that he observed, including bacteria, protists, and microscopic animals, as animalcules.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] He published his observations in a series of letters to the Royal Society of London.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Bacteria were Leeuwenhoek's most remarkable microscopic discovery.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Their size was just at the limit of what his simple lenses could resolve, and, in one of the most striking hiatuses in the history of science, no one else would see them again for over a century.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] His observations also included protozoans, and his findings were looked at again in the light of the more recent findings of cell theory.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Christian Gottfried Ehrenberg introduced the word "bacterium" in 1828.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] In fact, his *Bacterium* was a genus that contained non-spore-forming rod-shaped bacteria, as opposed to *Bacillus*, a genus of spore-forming rod-shaped bacteria defined by Ehrenberg in 1835.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Louis Pasteur demonstrated in 1859 that the growth of microorganisms causes the fermentation process and that this growth is not due to spontaneous generation (yeasts and molds, commonly associated with fermentation, are not bacteria, but rather fungi).
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Along with his contemporary Robert Koch, Pasteur was an early advocate of the germ theory of disease.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Before them, Ignaz Semmelweis and Joseph Lister had realised the importance of sanitised hands in medical work.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Semmelweis, who in the 1840s formulated his rules for handwashing in the hospital, prior to the advent of germ theory, attributed disease to "decomposing animal organic matter".
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] His ideas were rejected and his book on the topic condemned by the medical community.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] After Lister, however, doctors started sanitising their hands in the 1870s.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Robert Koch, a pioneer in medical microbiology, worked on cholera, anthrax and tuberculosis.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] In his research into tuberculosis, Koch finally proved the germ theory, for which he received a Nobel Prize in 1905.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] In Koch's postulates, he set out criteria to test if an organism is the cause of a disease, and these postulates are still used today.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Ferdinand Cohn is said to be a founder of bacteriology, studying bacteria from 1870.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Cohn was the first to classify bacteria based on their morphology.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Though it was known in the nineteenth century that bacteria are the cause of many diseases, no effective antibacterial treatments were available.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] In 1910, Paul Ehrlich developed the first antibiotic, by changing dyes that selectively stained *Treponema pallidum*—the spirochaete that causes syphilis—into compounds that selectively killed the pathogen.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] Ehrlich, who had been awarded a 1908 Nobel Prize for his work on immunology, pioneered the use of stains to detect and identify bacteria, with his work being the basis of the Gram stain and the Ziehl–Neelsen stain.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] A major step forward in the study of bacteria came in 1977 when Carl Woese recognised that archaea have a separate line of evolutionary descent from bacteria.
[src:strain-biology/bacteria-p02] This new phylogenetic taxonomy depended on the sequencing of 16S ribosomal RNA and divided prokaryotes into two evolutionary domains, as part of the three-domain system.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] In biology, a **strain** is a genetic variant, a subtype or a culture within a biological species.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] Strains are often seen as inherently artificial concepts, characterized by a specific intent for genetic isolation.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] This is most easily observed in microbiology where strains are derived from a single cell colony and are typically quarantined by the physical constraints of a Petri dish.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] Strains are also commonly referred to within virology, botany, and with rodents used in experimental studies.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] Prokaryotes (bacteria and archaea) have a vertical pattern of inheritance, with the exception of horizontal gene transfer events.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] The concept of a strain is traditionally based on cell culture lineage: the *Prokaryotic Code* defines a strain as the group "of the descendants of a single isolation in pure culture".
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] Accordingly, prokaryotes in the same strain are expected to have minimal phenotypic and genetic differences.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] (There has been some complication in the case of lost records about culture lineages.) A strain can be identified by a name assigned by some author (e.g.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] "B6", "natto"), or by the abbreviation of a culture collection followed by a number (e.g.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] The above fits well for artificial strains, often constructed in labs via mutagenesis followed by selection, or through more direct genetic modification.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] In biotechnology, microbial strains have been constructed to establish metabolic pathways suitable for treating a variety of applications.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] Historically, a major effort of metabolic research has been devoted to the field of biofuel production.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] *Escherichia coli* is most common species for prokaryotic strain engineering.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] Scientists have succeeded in establishing viable minimal genomes from which new strains can be developed.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] These minimal strains provide a near guarantee that experiments on genes outside the minimal framework will not be effected by non-essential pathways.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] Optimized strains of *E. coli* are typically used for this application.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] *E. coli* are also often used as a chassis for the expression of simple proteins.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] These strains, such as BL21, are genetically modified to minimize protease activity, hence enabling potential for high efficiency industrial scale protein production.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] The concept of a *strain* has also been expanded *ad hoc* to natural, uncultured populations such as those identified by metagenomics.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] However, this kind of use reveals an issue in the traditional definition of a strain: when a bacterium is transferred from a wild environment to culture, it often exhibits phenotypic changes due to adaptation, yet the wild and lab versions are not usually considered separate strains.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] An objective definition of a strain, independent from records and only based on the genome, has been proposed to solve the problem of lost records and natural/lab phenotype change.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] Rodriguez *et al.* (2024) found that the average nucleotide identity (ANI) between microbe genome pairs have a natural gap at 99.2%–99.8%, in addition to the previously known 95% species-level gap.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] They further found that using the ANI cutoffs of 99.5% or 99.8% both produce "strain" assignments that agree well with historical assignments.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] Fungi and plants are both governed by the *Botanical Code*.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] As a result, the term "strain" has no official taxonomic meaning.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] In common usage, the concept of a "strain" is similar to the prokaryotic one (descendants of a single isolation in pure culture).
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] The practice of naming is also similar to the prokaryotic case (e.g.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] Strains of yeasts are the most common subjects of eukaryotic genetic modification, especially with respect to industrial fermentation.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] With the exception of recombination events, viruses have a vertical pattern of inheritance, making for an obvious borrowing of the *strain* concept from microbiology.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] However, significant divergence has since happened: it has been said that "there is no universally accepted definition for the terms 'strain', 'variant', and 'isolate' in the virology community, and most virologists simply copy the usage of terms from others".
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] Some particular groups of viruses have a clear definition of a "strain".
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] The Orthomyxoviridae (flu viruses) have a standard strain nomenclature by the WHO.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] An example is "A/chicken/Nakorn-Patom/Thailand/CU-K2/04(H5N1)".
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] See Influenza § Influenza virus nomenclature.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] The WHO nomenclature does not define the term *strain*.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] Throughout the document it has a meaning similar to "isolate".
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] Scientists have modified isolates of viruses in order to study their behavior, as in the case of the H5N1 influenza virus.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] While funding for such research has aroused controversy at times due to safety concerns, leading to a temporary pause, it has subsequently proceeded.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] The live attenuated influenza vaccine is made by swapping the surface antigen genes (HA, NA) of a human flu isolate into a non-human flu isolate that replicates poorly at human body temperature.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] The resulting virus still replicates poorly in humans like its non-human parent.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] However, the surface antigen it carries will teach the recipient's immune system about the corresponding human flu isolate.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] The term has no official ranking status in botany; the term refers to the collective descendants produced from a common ancestor that share a uniform morphological or physiological character.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] A strain is a designated group of offspring that are either descended from a modified plant (produced by conventional breeding or by biotechnological means), or which result from genetic mutation.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] A laboratory mouse or rat strain is a group of animals that is genetically uniform.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] Strains are used in laboratory experiments.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] Mouse strains can be inbred, mutated, or genetically modified, while rat strains are usually inbred.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] A given inbred rodent population is considered genetically identical after 20 generations of sibling-mating.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] Many rodent strains have been developed for a variety of disease models, and they are also often used to test drug toxicity.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] The common fruit fly (*Drosophila melanogaster*) was among the first organisms used for genetic analysis, has a simple genome, and is very well understood.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] It has remained a popular model organism for many other reasons, like the ease of its breeding and maintenance, and the speed and volume of its reproduction.
[src:strain-biology/strain-biology] Various specific strains have been developed, including a flightless version with stunted wings (also used in the pet trade as live food for small reptiles and amphibians).
